92341594-2f12-4d27-ba78-58bfc5cbc724	345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77	3e6294d7-e8ef-4005-a670-64db9bbdf3c0	ST-21	feature	Update workflow initialization to load and store full story context	## Objective\nModify the workflow initialization process to load complete story context using the new centralized loader and store it in WorkflowRun metadata for access throughout workflow execution.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. **Update execute_story_with_workflow.ts**:\n   - Replace minimal story query (lines 56-62) with call to `loadStoryWithFullContext()`\n   - Store complete context in `WorkflowRun.metadata.storyContext` (during workflow run creation, lines 126-139)\n   - Update `executionContext` object to reference full context data\n   - Ensure backward compatibility with existing workflows\n\n2. **Metadata Structure**:\n   - Store as: `metadata: { storyContext: StoryFullContext, ...existing fields }`\n   - Ensure JSON serialization works correctly\n   - Validate metadata size is acceptable for database storage\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `execute_story_with_workflow` calls `loadStoryWithFullContext()`\n- [ ] Full story context stored in `WorkflowRun.metadata.storyContext`\n- [ ] Execution context updated to use loaded data\n- [ ] Workflow runs successfully with enhanced metadata\n- [ ] No breaking changes to existing workflows\n- [ ] Integration test verifies context stored correctly\n\n## Technical Notes\n\nFile: `backend/src/mcp/servers/execution/execute_story_with_workflow.ts`\n\nDepends on: Story for centralized context loader (ST-20)	planning	8	\N	5	\N	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-18 14:25:14.688	2025-11-18 14:25:14.688	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	\N	\N	\N	0
8859be52-66be-4e0f-89b7-ca6818cccc06	345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77	3e6294d7-e8ef-4005-a670-64db9bbdf3c0	ST-22	feature	Enhance get_workflow_context to return full story context	## Objective\nModify the `get_workflow_context` MCP tool to include the complete story context from WorkflowRun metadata, making it available to coordinators and components.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. **Update get_workflow_context.ts**:\n   - Extract `storyContext` from `workflowRun.metadata`\n   - Add `storyContext` field to response object\n   - Update TypeScript return type to include `storyContext: StoryFullContext`\n   - Handle cases where metadata might not have storyContext (older workflows)\n\n2. **Response Structure**:\n   ```typescript\n   {\n     workflowRun: {...},\n     coordinator: {...},\n     components: [...],\n     previousOutputs: {...},\n     storyContext: StoryFullContext  // NEW\n   }\n   ```\n\n3. **Backward Compatibility**:\n   - Return null or minimal context for workflows created before this feature\n   - Add clear comment in response when context unavailable\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `get_workflow_context` returns `storyContext` field\n- [ ] Context extracted from `workflowRun.metadata.storyContext`\n- [ ] Return type updated to include new field\n- [ ] Handles old workflows gracefully\n- [ ] MCP tool description updated\n- [ ] Integration test verifies context retrieval\n\n## Technical Notes\n\nFile: `backend/src/mcp/servers/execution/get_workflow_context.ts`\n\nDepends on: Story for workflow initialization update (ST-21)	planning	8	\N	3	\N	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-18 14:25:14.993	2025-11-18 14:25:14.993	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	\N	\N	\N	0
c2f2331d-44d5-4023-9207-af981c89cc9b	345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77	9ecdbb94-28b7-4358-94f0-a7280f466227	ST-7	bug	Fix metrics endpoint returning "No metrics found" error	**Bug Report**\n\n**Error:** No metrics found for project 345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77\n\n**Expected Behavior:** Metrics should be accessible and return valid data for the project.\n\n**Actual Behavior:** API returns error indicating no metrics found, preventing access to all metrics data.\n\n**Priority:** High - metrics are critical for production monitoring\n\n**Additional Notes:**\n- Code coverage metrics were working flaky before this issue\n- Need to verify data correctness after fix, especially code coverage calculations	done	8	3	6	\N	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 15:15:25.985	2025-11-17 15:36:01.74	# Technical Architecture Document - ST-7\n\n## 1. Problem Analysis\n\n### Root Causes Identified\n\n**Primary Issue: Inconsistent Empty State Handling**\n- `getFolderHierarchy()` at line 322 throws `NotFoundException` when CodeMetrics table is empty\n- `get_project_health` MCP handler throws error at line 74 when no metrics exist\n- Other methods return graceful defaults (empty arrays, zero-valued objects)\n\n**Secondary Issue: Flaky Code Coverage Calculations**\n- 5-minute time windows at lines 647-655 and 810-812 assume synchronized timestamps\n- If CodeAnalysisWorker writes metrics over longer periods, comparisons fail\n- Returns misleading results (all zeros) when metrics span different time ranges\n\n---\n\n## 2. System Design\n\n### Design Principle: Graceful Degradation\nAll metrics endpoints MUST follow this pattern:\n1. **No data exists**: Return structured empty/default response with metadata\n2. **Partial data**: Return available data with warning flags\n3. **Error conditions**: Only throw for invalid inputs (bad project ID, invalid params)\n\n### Architecture Pattern: Null Object Pattern\n```typescript\n// Standard empty response structure\ninterface EmptyMetricsResponse {\n  data: T;                    // Zero-valued or empty structured data\n  metadata: {\n    hasData: boolean;\n    reason?: string;\n    recommendation?: string;\n  };\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Data Model Changes\n\n**NO SCHEMA CHANGES REQUIRED** - This is error handling fix only.\n\nThe existing schema supports the fix:\n- CodeMetrics table structure remains unchanged\n- No new columns or indexes needed\n\n---\n\n## 4. API Contract Specifications\n\n### 4.1 GET /code-metrics/project/:projectId/hierarchy\n**Current Behavior**: Throws 404 NotFoundException when no metrics\n**New Behavior**: Returns empty hierarchy structure\n\n```typescript\n// Empty response structure\n{\n  path: '',\n  name: 'root',\n  type: 'folder',\n  metrics: {\n    fileCount: 0,\n    totalLoc: 0,\n    avgComplexity: 0,\n    avgCognitiveComplexity: 0,\n    avgMaintainability: 0,\n    avgCoverage: 0,\n    avgRiskScore: 0,\n    uncoveredFiles: 0,\n    criticalIssues: 0,\n    healthScore: 0,\n  },\n  children: [],\n}\n```\n\n### 4.2 MCP Tool: get_project_health\n**Current Behavior**: Throws error when no metrics\n**New Behavior**: Returns structured response with warning\n\n```json\n{\n  "project": {\n    "id": "projectId",\n    "name": "Project Name",\n    "totalFiles": 0,\n    "totalLoc": 0\n  },\n  "health": {\n    "score": 0,\n    "rating": "NoData"\n  },\n  "hasData": false,\n  "message": "No code metrics found. Run code analysis worker to populate metrics.",\n  "recommendation": "Use triggerAnalysis API or run CodeAnalysisWorker"\n}\n```\n\n### 4.3 All Other Metrics Endpoints\nAlready return graceful defaults - NO CHANGES NEEDED:\n- `getProjectMetrics()` - Returns zero-valued ProjectMetricsDto\n- `getAnalysisStatus()` - Returns `{ status: 'not_found' }`\n- `getAnalysisComparison()` - Returns zero-valued comparison\n- `getCodeIssues()` - Returns empty array\n- `getFileHotspots()` - Returns empty array\n- `getCoverageGaps()` - Returns empty array\n\n---\n\n## 5. Implementation Requirements\n\n### 5.1 Fix getFolderHierarchy() - PRIORITY 1\n**Location**: `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.service.ts:316-386`\n\n**Change**: Replace lines 321-322 exception throw with:\n```typescript\nif (metrics.length === 0) {\n  return {\n    path: '',\n    name: 'root',\n    type: 'folder',\n    metrics: this.createEmptyMetrics(),\n    children: [],\n  };\n}\n```\n\n### 5.2 Fix get_project_health MCP Handler - PRIORITY 1\n**Location**: `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/mcp/servers/code-quality/get_project_health.ts:73-77`\n\n**Change**: Replace error throw with graceful response:\n```typescript\nif (allMetrics.length === 0) {\n  return {\n    content: [{\n      type: 'text',\n      text: JSON.stringify({\n        project: { id: projectId, name: project.name, totalFiles: 0, totalLoc: 0 },\n        health: { score: 0, rating: 'NoData' },\n        hasData: false,\n        message: 'No code metrics found. Run code analysis worker first.',\n        recommendation: 'Use POST /code-metrics/project/:projectId/analyze or run CodeAnalysisWorker manually',\n        metrics: { complexity: { avg: 0 }, maintainability: { avg: 0 }, churn: { avg: 0 }, codeSmells: { total: 0, perFile: 0 } },\n        folders: [],\n        subfolders: [],\n        criticalHotspots: [],\n        insights: ['No metrics data available. Please run code analysis first.'],\n        recommendations: ['1. Configure project repository path', '2. Run code analysis worker to scan codebase'],\n      }, null, 2)\n    }]\n  };\n}\n```\n\n### 5.3 Fix Code Coverage Flakiness - PRIORITY 2\n**Issue**: 5-minute time windows assume all metrics have synchronized timestamps\n\n**Solution**: Use analysis batch identification instead of time windows\n```typescript\n// Find metrics from the SAME analysis batch (same lastAnalyzedAt timestamp)\nconst currentBatchTime = mostRecentMetric.lastAnalyzedAt;\nconst currentMetrics = await this.prisma.codeMetrics.findMany({\n  where: {\n    projectId,\n    lastAnalyzedAt: currentBatchTime,  // Exact match, not window\n  },\n});\n```\n\n**Alternative Approach** (if timestamps vary within batch):\n- Use `analysisVersion` or `batchId` field (would require schema change - defer to future story)\n- Increase window to 30 minutes (quick fix, not recommended)\n- Group by date (DATE(lastAnalyzedAt)) instead of exact time\n\n**Recommended Quick Fix**: Widen time window to 30 minutes for robustness:\n```typescript\nconst timeWindow = 30 * 60 * 1000; // 30 minutes instead of 5\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Integration Points\n\n### 6.1 Frontend Components\nNo changes needed - frontend already handles empty/error states\n\n### 6.2 MCP Tools Affected\n- `get_project_health` - Direct fix required\n- `get_file_health` - Uses getFileDetail() which throws 404 for missing file (CORRECT behavior)\n- `get_architect_insights` - Uses get_project_health internally, will benefit from fix\n\n### 6.3 Worker Integration\n- CodeAnalysisWorker populates CodeMetrics table\n- This fix handles the case when worker hasn't run yet\n\n---\n\n## 7. Performance Considerations\n\n### Impact: MINIMAL\n- No additional database queries\n- No new indexes required\n- Early return for empty case (faster execution)\n\n### Monitoring\n- Add logging when returning empty metrics state\n- Track frequency of "no metrics" responses to identify misconfigured projects\n\n---\n\n## 8. Security Implications\n\n### No Security Impact\n- No authentication changes\n- No authorization changes\n- No new attack vectors\n- Returns safe default values\n\n---\n\n## 9. Testing Requirements\n\n### Unit Tests\n1. `getFolderHierarchy()` returns empty structure when no metrics\n2. `get_project_health` returns graceful response when no metrics\n3. Verify response structure matches DTO contracts\n\n### Integration Tests\n1. API endpoint returns 200 (not 404) when metrics empty\n2. MCP tool returns valid JSON response when metrics empty\n3. Frontend handles empty metrics gracefully\n\n### Edge Cases\n1. Project exists but no metrics analyzed\n2. Partial metrics (some files analyzed, others not)\n3. Old metrics (beyond time range filter)\n\n---\n\n## 10. Implementation Order\n\n1. **Phase 1 - Critical Fix** (30 minutes)\n   - Fix `getFolderHierarchy()` empty state handling\n   - Fix `get_project_health` MCP handler\n\n2. **Phase 2 - Validation** (15 minutes)\n   - Add unit tests for empty state\n   - Verify API contracts\n\n3. **Phase 3 - Code Coverage Fix** (30 minutes)\n   - Widen time window to 30 minutes\n   - Add warning when time window mismatch detected\n\n4. **Phase 4 - Documentation** (15 minutes)\n   - Update API documentation with new behavior\n   - Document empty state response structures\n\n---\n\n## 11. Technical Debt Considerations\n\n### Current Technical Debt\n- No `batchId` or `analysisVersion` to group metrics from same analysis run\n- Time-window based grouping is fragile\n\n### Future Improvements (Out of Scope)\n- Add `analysisBatchId` to CodeMetrics table for reliable grouping\n- Implement historical snapshots for trend analysis\n- Add project-level analysis status tracking\n\n---\n\n## 12. Summary\n\n**Complexity Assessment**: MEDIUM (Technical Complexity: 6 is appropriate)\n- Fix is straightforward but touches core metrics infrastructure\n- Multiple files need coordinated changes\n- Must maintain backward compatibility\n- Testing is important to prevent regressions\n\n**Risk Level**: LOW\n- No schema changes\n- Returns safe default values\n- All changes are additive (graceful degradation)\n- No breaking API contract changes (HTTP 200 instead of 404)\n\n**Estimated Implementation Time**: 1.5-2 hours\n\n**Files to Modify**:\n1. `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.service.ts` (lines 321-322)\n2. `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/mcp/servers/code-quality/get_project_health.ts` (lines 73-77)\n	\N	f2279312-e340-409a-b317-0d4886a868ea	\N	\N	## Context Exploration Report\n\n### Story Summary\n**Story ST-7: Fix metrics endpoint returning "No metrics found" error**\n- Error: "No metrics found for project 345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77"\n- Impact: Metrics endpoints return errors, blocking access to all metrics data for production monitoring\n- Business Impact: 8 (Critical - metrics required for monitoring)\n- Technical Complexity: 6 (Moderate - involves query logic and database relationships)\n\n---\n\n## Root Cause Analysis\n\n### Error Location Found\n**File:** `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.service.ts` (Line 322)\n\n```typescript\nif (metrics.length === 0) {\n  throw new NotFoundException(`No metrics found for project ${projectId}`);\n}\n```\n\nThis error is thrown in the `getFolderHierarchy()` method when no CodeMetrics records exist for the project.\n\n---\n\n## Relevant Files Identified\n\n### Primary Metrics Services\n1. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/metrics/metrics.service.ts`** (670 lines)\n   - Handles workflow and component metrics aggregation\n   - Methods: `getWorkflowMetrics()`, `getComponentMetrics()`, `getTrends()`, `compareWorkflows()`, `getWeeklyAggregations()`\n   - Key issue: Returns empty arrays `[]` when no runs found (graceful), but other endpoints may not\n\n2. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/metrics/metrics.controller.ts`** (96 lines)\n   - Exposes REST endpoints: `/workflows`, `/components`, `/trends`, `/comparisons`, `/weekly`\n   - All protected with JWT auth\n   - Delegates to MetricsService\n\n3. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.service.ts`** (970 lines)\n   - Provides code quality metrics from CodeMetrics table\n   - **THROWS ERROR** at line 322 in `getFolderHierarchy()` method\n   - Methods: `getProjectMetrics()`, `getFileHotspots()`, `getFileDetail()`, `getTrendData()`, `getCodeIssues()`, `getFolderHierarchy()` (ERROR HERE)\n   - Missing data handling in several methods\n\n4. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/agent-metrics/agent-metrics.service.ts`** (1362 lines)\n   - Advanced metrics: framework comparison, weekly analysis, story execution details, per-agent analytics\n   - Methods: `getFrameworkComparison()`, `getWeeklyAnalysis()`, `getStoryExecutionDetails()`, `getPerAgentAnalytics()`, `getWorkflowMetrics()`, `compareWorkflows()`\n   - Issues: Some methods throw "not yet implemented" errors (lines 616, 785)\n   - Comprehensive workflow metrics implementation with aggregation by workflow/story/epic/agent (lines 825-946)\n\n### Database Tables Involved\n1. **WorkflowRun** (schema.prisma lines 619-678)\n   - Main execution tracking table\n   - Fields: status, startedAt, totalTokens, totalLocGenerated, totalTestsAdded, estimatedCost, durationSeconds\n   - Relations: project, workflow, story, epic, coordinator, componentRuns\n\n2. **ComponentRun** (schema.prisma lines 681-786)\n   - Individual component execution within workflow\n   - Fields: tokensInput, tokensOutput, durationSeconds, cost, success, locGenerated, testsAdded\n   - ST-27 metrics: cache metrics, code impact, quality metrics\n\n3. **CodeMetrics** (schema.prisma lines 189-217)\n   - Code quality metrics per file\n   - Fields: linesOfCode, cyclomaticComplexity, maintainabilityIndex, testCoverage, riskScore\n\n4. **MetricsAggregation** (schema.prisma lines 896-920)\n   - Pre-calculated metrics for performance (currently appears empty based on error patterns)\n\n5. **OtelEvent** (schema.prisma lines 789-828)\n   - OpenTelemetry event tracking (NEW - ST-27 metrics initiative)\n   - Replaces older token-based metrics collection\n\n### Controllers/Routes\n1. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/metrics/metrics.controller.ts`**\n   - Routes: GET `/projects/:projectId/metrics/workflows`, `/components`, `/trends`, `/weekly`\n   - POST `/projects/:projectId/metrics/comparisons`\n\n2. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.controller.ts`**\n   - Routes for code quality metrics (also references getFolderHierarchy that throws error)\n\n3. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/agent-metrics/agent-metrics.controller.ts`**\n   - Advanced analytics endpoints\n\n---\n\n## Key Dependencies Map\n\n```\nMetricsController\n├── MetricsService\n│   ├── PrismaService.workflowRun.findMany() - DEPENDENCY 1\n│   ├── PrismaService.componentRun.findMany() - DEPENDENCY 2\n│   └── PrismaService.testCase.count() - DEPENDENCY 3\n│\nAgentMetricsService\n├── PrismaService.workflowRun.findMany()\n├── PrismaService.run.findMany()\n├── PrismaService.story.findMany()\n└── PrismaService.testCase.count()\n│\nCodeMetricsService (ERROR SOURCE)\n├── PrismaService.codeMetrics.findMany() - Returns empty array\n└── Throws NotFoundException when metrics.length === 0 (Line 322)\n│\nWorkflowRunsService\n├── PrismaService.workflowRun.findFirst()\n├── PrismaService.workflowRun.findMany()\n└── PrismaService.componentRun.count()\n```\n\n---\n\n## Critical Issues & Root Causes\n\n### Issue 1: CodeMetrics Empty Table\n**Location:** `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.service.ts:322`\n\n**Problem:**\n```typescript\nconst metrics = await this.prisma.codeMetrics.findMany({\n  where: { projectId },\n  lastAnalyzedAt: { gte: startDate },\n});\n\nif (metrics.length === 0) {\n  throw new NotFoundException(`No metrics found for project ${projectId}`);\n}\n```\n\n**Root Cause:** \n- CodeMetrics table is likely empty because code analysis has never been run or data was not populated\n- No graceful fallback when metrics don't exist yet\n- Inconsistent error handling compared to MetricsService (which returns empty arrays)\n\n### Issue 2: Metrics Data Consistency Across Services\n**Services using different patterns:**\n1. **MetricsService**: Returns empty arrays `[]` when no data (lines 123-124, graceful)\n2. **CodeMetricsService**: Throws `NotFoundException` when empty (line 322, hard error)\n3. **AgentMetricsService**: Returns empty metrics objects when no data (lines 155-166)\n\n**Impact:** Client code cannot consistently handle metrics endpoints\n\n### Issue 3: Coverage Calculation Issues\nPer story description: "Code coverage metrics were working flaky before this issue"\n\n**Investigation findings:**\n- Coverage data stored in CommitFile.coverageAfter and CodeMetrics.testCoverage\n- AgentMetricsService calculates coverage from commits (line 676: `prevWeightedCoverage`)\n- CodeMetricsService uses testCoverage field directly (line 65)\n- **Issue:** Flaky coverage likely because:\n  - Data might not be populated from CI systems properly\n  - Different sources (commit data vs code metrics table) may conflict\n  - Historical data comparison uses time windows that might miss data (line 646: 5-minute window)\n\n---\n\n## Database Query Patterns\n\n### Pattern 1: WorkflowRun Aggregation (MetricsService)\n```typescript\n// Good pattern - handles empty gracefully\nconst runs = await prisma.workflowRun.findMany({\n  where: { projectId, status: RunStatus.completed },\n  include: { workflow: true }\n});\n\nif (runs.length === 0) {\n  return []; // Returns empty array, not an error\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 2: CodeMetrics Query (CodeMetricsService)\n```typescript\n// Bad pattern - throws error on empty\nconst metrics = await prisma.codeMetrics.findMany({\n  where: { projectId }\n});\n\nif (metrics.length === 0) {\n  throw new NotFoundException(...); // Hard failure\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 3: Historical Data Comparison (CodeMetricsService)\n```typescript\n// Problematic pattern - 5-minute window might be too narrow\nconst previousMetrics = await prisma.codeMetrics.findMany({\n  where: {\n    projectId,\n    lastAnalyzedAt: {\n      gte: new Date(previousAnalysisTime.getTime() - 5 * 60 * 1000),\n      lte: new Date(previousAnalysisTime.getTime() + 5 * 60 * 1000)\n    }\n  }\n});\n\nif (previousMetrics.length === 0) {\n  return { /* zeros */ }; // Falls back to zeros\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Test Coverage Findings\n\n### Test Files Located\n1. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/metrics/__tests__/metrics.service.test.ts`** (166 lines)\n   - Tests: `getWeeklyAggregations()`, `getWorkflowMetrics()`, `getTrends()`\n   - Good coverage for empty data handling\n   - **Note:** Mocks all Prisma calls, doesn't test actual database queries\n\n2. **`/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/workflow-runs/__tests__/workflow-runs.service.test.ts`**\n   - Tests: `getActiveWorkflowForProject()`, component run tracking\n   - TC-WORKFLOW-TRACKING-001 test case\n\n3. **MCP Metrics Tests** (2 test files found):\n   - `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/mcp/servers/metrics/__tests__/get_component_actual_metrics.test.ts`\n   - `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/mcp/servers/metrics/__tests__/get_workflow_metrics_breakdown.test.ts`\n\n### Test Coverage Gaps\n- No tests for CodeMetricsService empty data handling\n- No integration tests for actual database queries\n- No tests for code coverage calculation logic (why metrics are "flaky")\n\n---\n\n## Technical Constraints\n\n1. **Database Schema Complexity**\n   - Multiple metrics sources: WorkflowRun, ComponentRun, CodeMetrics, Run, MetricsAggregation, OtelEvent\n   - Relations not always enforced (some metrics might not link to stories)\n   - No constraints preventing orphaned metrics records\n\n2. **Time-based Windowing Issues**\n   - 5-minute windows for historical comparisons (line 646) too restrictive\n   - Analysis timestamps may not align if jobs run asynchronously\n   - Daylight saving time boundary issues in weekly/monthly aggregations\n\n3. **Pre-calculation vs. Real-time**\n   - MetricsAggregation table exists but may not be populated\n   - System queries live data instead of pre-calculated aggregations\n   - Performance impact as project grows\n\n4. **Incomplete Metrics Implementation**\n   - AgentMetricsService: `getWeeklyAnalysis()` throws "not implemented" (line 616)\n   - AgentMetricsService: `getPerAgentAnalytics()` throws "not implemented" (line 785)\n   - Overhead analysis returns undefined (line 537)\n\n---\n\n## Recommended Implementation Approach\n\n### Phase 1: Immediate Fixes (High Priority)\n1. **Standardize Empty Data Handling**\n   - Change CodeMetricsService `getFolderHierarchy()` to return empty structure instead of throwing error (line 322)\n   - Match behavior of MetricsService (return empty arrays/objects)\n   - Apply same pattern to all metrics endpoints\n\n2. **Add Health Check Endpoint**\n   - New endpoint: `GET /projects/:projectId/metrics/health`\n   - Returns: last analysis timestamp, metrics table row counts\n   - Helps diagnose "no metrics" issues\n\n### Phase 2: Root Cause Investigation (Medium Priority)\n1. **Data Population Verification**\n   - Verify code analysis job populates CodeMetrics table\n   - Check if WorkflowRun metrics are calculated on completion\n   - Audit which projects have metrics vs. which don't\n\n2. **Fix Code Coverage Flakiness**\n   - Consolidate coverage sources (commit vs. code metrics)\n   - Add validation to ensure coverage values are within 0-100 range\n   - Implement caching for coverage calculations\n   - Add unit tests for coverage calculation logic\n\n### Phase 3: Long-term Improvements (Lower Priority)\n1. **Implement MetricsAggregation**\n   - Use pre-calculated aggregations for performance\n   - Background job to refresh daily/weekly/monthly aggregations\n   - Prevents real-time query bottlenecks\n\n2. **Complete Remaining Metrics Methods**\n   - Implement `getWeeklyAnalysis()`\n   - Implement `getPerAgentAnalytics()`\n   - Implement overhead analysis\n\n3. **Migrate to OtelEvent**\n   - Replace Run/old metrics with OtelEvent-based metrics\n   - Better tool-level tracking\n   - Align with ST-27 metrics initiative\n\n---\n\n## Files to Modify\n\n**CRITICAL:**\n- `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.service.ts` - Remove error throwing at line 322\n\n**HIGH PRIORITY:**\n- `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/metrics/metrics.service.ts` - Ensure consistent empty handling\n- `/opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/agent-metrics/agent-metrics.service.ts` - Complete implementations\n- Database initialization/migration scripts\n\n**MEDIUM PRIORITY:**\n- Test files for comprehensive coverage\n- Code coverage calculation logic\n- Historical comparison time windows\n\n**NEW FILES TO CREATE:**\n- Metrics health check endpoint\n- Data population diagnostics script\n- Integration tests for database queries	\N	0	\N	\N	\N	0
b4f7ab9f-769c-4cf5-87dc-dd8ca463c4e5	345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77	9ecdbb94-28b7-4358-94f0-a7280f466227	ST-2	feature	Comprehensive Agent Statistics Tracking System	## Overview\n\nImplement comprehensive metrics tracking for AI agent execution to provide deep insights into agent performance, cost efficiency, and code impact.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n### 1. ComponentRun Schema Extensions (15+ new fields)\n\n**Session Tracking:**\n- `sessionId` - Claude Code session ID for OTEL mapping\n\n**Cache Metrics:**\n- `tokensCacheRead` - Tokens read from cache\n- `tokensCacheWrite` - Tokens written to cache\n- `cacheHits` / `cacheMisses` - Cache hit/miss counts\n- `cacheHitRate` - Percentage (0.0-1.0)\n\n**Code Impact Metrics:**\n- `linesAdded` / `linesDeleted` / `linesModified` - Code changes\n- `complexityBefore` / `complexityAfter` - Cyclomatic complexity\n- `coverageBefore` / `coverageAfter` - Test coverage percentage\n\n**Quality Metrics:**\n- `errorRate` - Failed tools / total tools\n- `successRate` - Successful completions\n- `toolBreakdown` - JSON: `{toolName: {calls, errors, avgDuration}}`\n\n**Agent Behavior:**\n- `contextSwitches` - File/domain changes\n- `explorationDepth` - Files analyzed before implementing\n\n**Cost & Performance:**\n- `costBreakdown` - JSON: `{input: $, output: $, cache: $}`\n- `modelId` - Model used (e.g., claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929)\n- `temperature` - Model temperature setting\n- `maxTokens` - Max tokens configuration\n- `stopReason` - end_turn, max_tokens, tool_use, error\n- `timeToFirstToken` - Seconds\n- `tokensPerSecond` - Throughput\n\n### 2. New OtelEvent Model\n\nOpenTelemetry event tracking for actual runtime metrics:\n- `sessionId` - Claude Code session identifier\n- `eventType` - claude_code.api_request, claude_code.tool_use, etc.\n- `toolName` - Read, Write, Edit, Bash, MCP tools\n- `toolParameters` - Tool input parameters\n- `toolDuration` - Execution time in seconds\n- `toolSuccess` / `toolError` - Success tracking\n- `processed` / `aggregatedAt` - Aggregation flags\n\n### 3. New Services\n\n**OTEL Ingestion Service** (`backend/src/services/otel-ingestion.service.ts`):\n- Receives and processes OpenTelemetry events\n- Maps events to workflow/component runs\n- Stores events in database\n\n**Metrics Aggregation Service** (`backend/src/services/metrics-aggregation.service.ts`):\n- Aggregates OTEL events into ComponentRun metrics\n- Calculates cache hit rates, error rates, throughput\n- Updates cost breakdowns\n\n### 4. New MCP Tools\n\nDirectory: `backend/src/mcp/servers/metrics/`\n- Tools for querying and analyzing agent metrics\n- Dashboard data endpoints\n- Performance comparison tools\n\n## Files Modified\n\n- `backend/prisma/schema.prisma` - Schema extensions\n- `backend/src/services/otel-ingestion.service.ts` - NEW\n- `backend/src/services/metrics-aggregation.service.ts` - NEW\n- `backend/src/mcp/servers/metrics/` - NEW directory\n- `backend/src/utils/` - NEW utilities directory\n\n## Status\n\nSchema changes were applied but database rebuild caused data loss. Schema is ready for re-deployment.	implementation	8	7	9	\N	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 10:06:50.485	2025-11-17 12:54:27.475	# Complete Live Metrics Architecture for ST-2\n\n## Overview\n\nThe challenge is **correlating OTEL events to specific workflow component runs**. Here's how the complete pipeline works:\n\n## Data Flow Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────┐\n│  VibeStudio Backend │\n│  (Workflow Engine)  │\n└──────────┬──────────┘\n           │ 1. Start Component Run\n           │    - Generate unique session ID\n           │    - Set OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES\n           ▼\n┌─────────────────────┐     OTEL Events      ┌──────────────────┐\n│    Claude Code      │ ─────────────────►   │   OTEL Collector │\n│   (spawned agent)   │                      │  (port 4317/4318)│\n│                     │     Includes:        └────────┬─────────┘\n│ ENV:                │     - session.id              │\n│ OTEL_RESOURCE_      │     - workflow_run_id         │ 2. Store & Route\n│  ATTRIBUTES=        │     - component_run_id        │\n│  workflow_run_id=X  │     - project_id              ▼\n│  component_run_id=Y │                      ┌──────────────────┐\n│  project_id=Z       │                      │   Storage Layer  │\n└─────────────────────┘                      │                  │\n                                             │  - ClickHouse    │\n                                             │  - Loki          │\n                                             │  - TimescaleDB   │\n                                             └────────┬─────────┘\n                                                      │\n                                                      │ 3. Query by\n                                                      │    component_run_id\n                                                      ▼\n                                             ┌──────────────────┐\n                                             │  VibeStudio      │\n                                             │  Metrics Service │\n                                             │                  │\n                                             │  Aggregates to   │\n                                             │  ComponentRun    │\n                                             └──────────────────┘\n```\n\n## Correlation Strategy: Injecting Workflow Metadata\n\n### The Key: `OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES`\n\nWhen we spawn a Claude Code agent for a component, we inject workflow context as **resource attributes**:\n\n```bash\nOTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES="workflow_run_id=<uuid>,component_run_id=<uuid>,project_id=<uuid>,component_name=Explore"\n```\n\nThese attributes are attached to **ALL** telemetry data (metrics and logs) from that session.\n\n### Implementation Flow\n\n```typescript\n// When starting a component agent:\nasync function spawnComponentAgent(componentRunId: string, workflowRunId: string, projectId: string) {\n  const env = {\n    ...process.env,\n    CLAUDE_CODE_ENABLE_TELEMETRY: '1',\n    OTEL_METRICS_EXPORTER: 'otlp',\n    OTEL_LOGS_EXPORTER: 'otlp',\n    OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT: 'http://otel-collector:4317',\n    OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES: `workflow_run_id=${workflowRunId},component_run_id=${componentRunId},project_id=${projectId}`,\n    OTEL_METRICS_INCLUDE_SESSION_ID: 'true',\n  };\n  \n  // Spawn Claude Code with these env vars\n  const process = spawn('claude', ['--prompt', taskPrompt], { env });\n  \n  // Record the session.id → component_run_id mapping\n  const sessionId = await extractSessionId(process);\n  await otelService.mapSessionToComponent(sessionId, componentRunId);\n}\n```\n\n## What Data Gets Collected\n\n### Metrics (Prometheus/ClickHouse)\n| Metric | Type | Key Attributes |\n|--------|------|----------------|\n| `claude_code.token.usage` | Counter | `model`, `type` (input/output/cache), `workflow_run_id`, `component_run_id` |\n| `claude_code.cost.usage` | Counter | `model`, `workflow_run_id`, `component_run_id` |\n| `claude_code.lines_of_code.count` | Counter | `type` (added/removed), `component_run_id` |\n| `claude_code.active_time.total` | Gauge | `session.id`, `component_run_id` |\n\n### Events (Loki/ClickHouse)\n| Event | Key Attributes |\n|-------|----------------|\n| `claude_code.api_request` | `model`, `cost_usd`, `input_tokens`, `output_tokens`, `cache_read_tokens`, `duration_ms` |\n| `claude_code.tool_result` | `tool_name`, `success`, `duration_ms`, `error`, `tool_parameters` |\n| `claude_code.user_prompt` | `prompt_length`, (redacted by default) |\n| `claude_code.api_error` | `error`, `status_code`, `attempt` |\n\n## Storage Options\n\n### Option A: ClickHouse (Recommended for High Volume)\n```sql\n-- Query all tool usage for a component run\nSELECT \n  tool_name,\n  COUNT(*) as calls,\n  SUM(CASE WHEN success = false THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as errors,\n  AVG(duration_ms) as avg_duration_ms\nFROM otel_logs\nWHERE \n  resource.workflow_run_id = '<uuid>'\n  AND resource.component_run_id = '<uuid>'\n  AND event_name = 'claude_code.tool_result'\nGROUP BY tool_name;\n```\n\n### Option B: Loki + LogQL\n```logql\n{job="claude-code"} \n| json \n| workflow_run_id="<uuid>" \n| component_run_id="<uuid>"\n| event_name="claude_code.tool_result"\n| line_format "{{.tool_name}}: {{.duration_ms}}ms"\n```\n\n### Option C: TimescaleDB (Time-series optimized PostgreSQL)\nCan store directly in our existing PostgreSQL with TimescaleDB extension.\n\n## OTEL Collector Configuration\n\n```yaml\nreceivers:\n  otlp:\n    protocols:\n      grpc:\n        endpoint: 0.0.0.0:4317\n      http:\n        endpoint: 0.0.0.0:4318\n\nprocessors:\n  batch:\n    timeout: 10s\n    send_batch_size: 1000\n  \n  # Add VibeStudio-specific attributes\n  resource:\n    attributes:\n      - key: service.name\n        value: "vibestudio-agent"\n        action: upsert\n\nexporters:\n  # Option 1: ClickHouse\n  clickhouse:\n    endpoint: tcp://clickhouse:9000\n    database: otel\n    \n  # Option 2: Loki (for logs/events)\n  loki:\n    endpoint: http://loki:3100/loki/api/v1/push\n    \n  # Option 3: Our backend API (for real-time processing)\n  otlphttp:\n    endpoint: http://vibestudio-backend:3001/api/otel/ingest\n\nservice:\n  pipelines:\n    metrics:\n      receivers: [otlp]\n      processors: [batch, resource]\n      exporters: [clickhouse]\n    logs:\n      receivers: [otlp]\n      processors: [batch, resource]\n      exporters: [loki, otlphttp]  # Send to both for real-time + storage\n```\n\n## Implementation Steps\n\n### 1. Verify OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES Works\n```bash\n# Test that Claude Code respects custom resource attributes\nCLAUDE_CODE_ENABLE_TELEMETRY=1 \\\nOTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:4317 \\\nOTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES="test_id=123,component=test" \\\nclaude --print "Hello world"\n\n# Check collector logs for test_id=123\n```\n\n### 2. Apply Database Migrations\n```bash\nDATABASE_URL="..." npx prisma migrate deploy\n```\n\n### 3. Set Up OTEL Collector\nEither:\n- **Local**: Docker container with our config\n- **Cloud**: Grafana Cloud / Datadog / Honeycomb\n\n### 4. Create Ingestion Endpoint\n```typescript\n// POST /api/otel/ingest\n@Post('ingest')\nasync ingestOtelEvent(@Body() event: OtelEventDto) {\n  // Extract workflow metadata from resource attributes\n  const workflowRunId = event.resource.attributes['workflow_run_id'];\n  const componentRunId = event.resource.attributes['component_run_id'];\n  \n  // Store in OtelEvent table\n  await this.otelService.ingestEvent({\n    ...event,\n    workflowRunId,\n    componentRunId,\n  });\n  \n  // Real-time aggregation to ComponentRun\n  await this.metricsAggregation.updateLiveMetrics(componentRunId);\n}\n```\n\n### 5. Modify Agent Spawning\nUpdate the Task tool (or coordinator) to inject OTEL environment variables when spawning Claude Code agents.\n\n## Alternative: Query Grafana/Loki Directly\n\nIf you prefer to keep data in Grafana stack:\n\n```typescript\n// Query Loki for metrics instead of storing in PostgreSQL\nclass LokiMetricsService {\n  async getComponentMetrics(componentRunId: string) {\n    const query = `\n      {job="claude-code"} \n      | json \n      | component_run_id="${componentRunId}"\n    `;\n    \n    const result = await this.lokiClient.query(query);\n    return this.aggregateMetrics(result);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Summary: What We Need\n\n1. **OTEL Collector** - Central ingestion point (Docker/Cloud)\n2. **Storage Backend** - ClickHouse/Loki/TimescaleDB for OTEL data\n3. **Session Correlation** - Inject `component_run_id` via `OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES`\n4. **Ingestion API** - (Optional) Direct HTTP endpoint for real-time processing\n5. **Query Layer** - Service to query/aggregate from storage into ComponentRun\n\n**The key insight**: By setting `OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES` when spawning Claude Code, all telemetry automatically gets tagged with our workflow context, making correlation trivial.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Test if Claude Code respects `OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES`\n2. Set up a Docker-based OTEL Collector\n3. Create the ingestion API endpoint\n4. Design the Grafana dashboard queries\n5. Implement agent spawning with OTEL env vars	\N	f2279312-e340-409a-b317-0d4886a868ea	# Business Analysis - ST-2\n\n## Stakeholders\n- Product Owner: Performance visibility & cost efficiency\n- Development Team: Actionable optimization metrics\n- Operations: Monitoring & alerting\n- Finance: Cost tracking & forecasting\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n### AC-1: OTEL Event Ingestion\n**Given** Claude Code runs with telemetry enabled\n**When** it emits OTEL event (api_request, tool_result)\n**Then** event stored in OtelEvent table with session_id, event_type, attributes\n\n### AC-2: Session Correlation\n**Given** component run starts with OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES\n**When** attributes include component_run_id\n**Then** all OTEL events linked to ComponentRun\n\n### AC-3: Cache Metrics\n**Given** OTEL events contain cache info\n**When** aggregation runs\n**Then** cacheHitRate = cacheHits / (cacheHits + cacheMisses)\n\n### AC-4: Tool Breakdown\n**Given** multiple tool_result events\n**When** aggregation completes\n**Then** toolBreakdown = {toolName: {calls, errors, avgDuration}}\n\n### AC-5: Cost Breakdown\n**Given** API requests with token counts\n**When** cost calculation runs\n**Then** costBreakdown = {input: $, output: $, cache: $} in USD\n\n### AC-6: Code Impact\n**Given** agent modifies files\n**When** execution completes\n**Then** linesAdded/Deleted/Modified populated\n\n## Risk Assessment\n- **High**: Session correlation missing events - Validate OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES\n- **Medium**: Migration failure - Backup database first\n- **Medium**: Storage overflow - Batch processing, retention policy\n\n## Success Metrics\n- 95%+ data completeness\n- <1s ingestion latency\n- <2s dashboard load (10K+ events)\n- Cost accuracy ±0.01%	\N	# Context Exploration Report - ST-2\n\n## Relevant Files (20+ files identified)\n\n### Core OTEL Infrastructure\n- `backend/src/services/otel-ingestion.service.ts` - Event ingestion\n- `backend/src/services/metrics-aggregation.service.ts` - Metrics aggregation\n- `backend/prisma/schema.prisma` - OtelEvent model + ComponentRun extensions (15+ fields)\n\n### MCP Metrics Tools\n- `backend/src/mcp/servers/metrics/get_component_actual_metrics.ts`\n- `backend/src/mcp/servers/metrics/get_workflow_metrics_breakdown.ts`\n- `backend/src/mcp/servers/metrics/get_agent_interaction_history.ts`\n\n### Key Schema Extensions\n- Cache: tokensCacheRead, tokensCacheWrite, cacheHits, cacheMisses, cacheHitRate\n- Code Impact: linesAdded/Deleted/Modified, complexity/coverage before/after\n- Quality: errorRate, successRate, toolBreakdown (JSON)\n- Performance: costBreakdown (JSON), modelId, timeToFirstToken, tokensPerSecond\n\n## Critical Gaps\n1. **Database migrations not applied** (3 pending)\n2. **No HTTP ingestion endpoint** for OTEL events\n3. **Session correlation** needs OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES injection\n4. **OTEL Collector** not configured (Docker setup needed)\n\n## Recommendations\n1. Apply migrations first\n2. Create POST /api/otel/events controller\n3. Configure OTEL Collector in Docker\n4. Implement session-to-component mapping	\N	0	# UI/UX Design - Metrics Dashboard\n\n## Key Components\n1. **Live Metrics Panel** - Real-time tokens, cost, tool calls, cache hit rate\n2. **Component Timeline** - Visual execution sequence with status colors\n3. **Tool Breakdown Chart** - Bar chart with success/error rates\n4. **Cost Analysis Widget** - Pie chart breakdown (input/output/cache)\n5. **Code Impact Summary** - Lines changed, complexity delta, coverage\n\n## Interaction Patterns\n- Auto-refresh: 5s polling\n- Click-to-drill-down: Component → Events\n- Hover tooltips for details\n- Time range selector: 1h, 24h, 7d, 30d\n\n## Responsive Design\n- Desktop: 3-column grid\n- Tablet: 2-column stacked\n- Mobile: Single column, collapsible\n\n## Existing Files\n- `frontend/src/pages/AgentMetricsDashboard.tsx` - Dashboard page exists\n- Theme-aware (dark/light mode)\n\n## Accessibility\n- ARIA labels, keyboard nav, contrast >4.5:1	\N	\N	0
61dcc46d-44ea-4f5e-8cdc-62dab73c4631	345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77	9ecdbb94-28b7-4358-94f0-a7280f466227	ST-4	bug	Fix styling to use light/dark theme on workflows and analytics pages	Update the following pages to properly support both light and dark themes:\n\n- /workflows - Workflows listing page\n- /analytics/workflow - Workflow analytics dashboard\n\nEnsure all components use theme-aware colors and CSS variables instead of hardcoded values for consistent appearance across both modes.	done	4	2	3	\N	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 13:33:09.589	2025-11-17 15:02:14.786	# Software Architecture Analysis for ST-4\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThis is a **frontend-only CSS class refactoring task** with zero backend, database, or API changes. The task involves replacing hard-coded Tailwind color classes with theme-aware CSS variable classes to support light/dark mode switching.\n\n---\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n### 1. Theme System Architecture\n\n**Current Implementation:**\n- Theme context at `/opt/stack/AIStudio/frontend/src/context/ThemeContext.tsx`\n- CSS variables defined in `/opt/stack/AIStudio/frontend/src/index.css`\n- Tailwind configuration maps CSS variables to utility classes in `/opt/stack/AIStudio/frontend/tailwind.config.js`\n- Theme switching via `data-theme="dark"` attribute on `document.documentElement`\n\n**Available Theme-Aware Classes:**\n- `text-fg` → foreground text (replaces `text-gray-700`, `text-gray-800`, `text-gray-900`)\n- `text-muted` → muted text (replaces `text-gray-500`, `text-gray-600`)\n- `bg-bg` → background (replaces `bg-white`)\n- `bg-bg-secondary` → secondary background (replaces `bg-gray-50`, `bg-gray-100`)\n- `bg-card` → card background (already used in some places)\n- `border-border` → borders (replaces `border-gray-200`, `border-gray-300`)\n\n### 2. File Modification Strategy\n\n**Order of Operations (dependency-aware):**\n\n1. **WorkflowRunsHistory.tsx** (4 fixes) - Simplest, no dependencies\n   - Lines 27, 39, 44, 49\n   - Status badge colors (needs dark mode variants)\n   - Spinner border color\n\n2. **WorkflowManagementView.tsx** (~11 fixes) - Intermediate complexity\n   - Lines 119, 125, 152, 179, 304, 347, 387\n   - Many already have dark mode variants (e.g., `bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900`)\n   - Should standardize to use CSS variables consistently\n   - Contains semantic colors (green/red/blue) that may need dark variants\n\n3. **WorkflowRunsTable.tsx** (45+ fixes) - Most complex\n   - Lines 45-53, 158, 166, 189, 191-214, 219, 251-330\n   - Table structure with headers, body, pagination\n   - Status badges without dark mode support\n   - Pagination controls with extensive hard-coded colors\n\n### 3. Replacement Patterns\n\n**Category A - Direct Replacements (Safe):**\n```\ntext-gray-700 → text-fg\ntext-gray-800 → text-fg\ntext-gray-500 → text-muted\ntext-gray-400 → text-muted\nbg-white → bg-card (for containers) OR bg-bg (for backgrounds)\nbg-gray-50 → bg-bg-secondary\nbg-gray-100 → bg-bg-secondary\nborder-gray-200 → border-border\nborder-gray-300 → border-border\nborder-gray-600 → border-border\n```\n\n**Category B - Semantic Colors (Require Dark Mode Variants):**\n```\n// Status badges must support both themes\nbg-green-100 text-green-800 → bg-green-100 dark:bg-green-900/30 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300\nbg-red-100 text-red-800 → bg-red-100 dark:bg-red-900/30 text-red-800 dark:text-red-300\nbg-blue-100 text-blue-800 → bg-blue-100 dark:bg-blue-900/30 text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300\nbg-gray-100 text-gray-800 → bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-300\n\n// Borders for badges\nborder-green-200 → border-green-200 dark:border-green-800\nborder-red-200 → border-red-200 dark:border-red-800\nborder-blue-200 → border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-800\n```\n\n**Category C - Interactive States:**\n```\nhover:bg-gray-50 → hover:bg-bg-secondary\n```\n\n### 4. Integration Points\n\n**No Component Props Affected:**\n- These are pure CSS class changes\n- No TypeScript interface changes required\n- No state management changes\n- No useTheme() hook needed (theme context already handles document-level switching)\n\n**Form Elements Already Handled:**\n- Input/select/textarea elements are auto-themed via `@layer components` in index.css\n- Only need to fix surrounding container colors\n\n### 5. Risk Assessment\n\n**Low Risk Factors:**\n- No functional logic changes\n- No state changes\n- No API changes\n- No database changes\n- Visual-only changes\n- All replacements are well-defined patterns\n\n**Potential Issues:**\n1. **Table contrast in dark mode** - Ensure `bg-white divide-y divide-gray-200` in tbody maintains readability\n2. **Hover states** - `hover:bg-gray-50` must work in dark mode (should be `hover:bg-bg-secondary`)\n3. **Badge readability** - Semantic colors (green/red/blue) need careful dark mode treatment\n\n### 6. Testing Strategy\n\n**Visual Testing (Required):**\n1. Toggle between light and dark mode on each page\n2. Check all status badges remain readable\n3. Verify table headers, rows, and pagination are clearly visible\n4. Ensure hover states provide clear feedback\n5. Test with both themes in:\n   - WorkflowManagementView (workflow cards + modal)\n   - WorkflowRunsTable (full table + pagination)\n   - WorkflowRunsHistory (inline badges)\n\n**Accessibility Verification:**\n- Contrast ratios meet WCAG AA (4.5:1 for text)\n- Focus states remain visible\n- Interactive elements distinguishable\n\n**Browser Testing:**\n- Chrome, Firefox, Safari (if available)\n- Check `data-theme` attribute propagation\n\n### 7. Rollback Strategy\n\n**Simple Git Revert:**\nSince these are isolated CSS class changes:\n- Changes are atomic per file\n- Can be reverted file-by-file if needed\n- No migrations or data changes to undo\n\n### 8. Technical Decisions Documentation\n\n**Q: Why CSS Variables over direct Tailwind colors?**\nA: CSS variables enable runtime theme switching without page reload. The theme context sets `data-theme` on the document root, and CSS variables automatically update. This is more maintainable than conditional class rendering.\n\n**Q: Why not use Tailwind's dark: modifier exclusively?**\nA: The project uses both approaches:\n- CSS variables for core semantic colors (fg, bg, muted, border)\n- `dark:` modifier for semantic status colors (green/red/blue) that need explicit different shades\nThis hybrid approach provides best maintainability while supporting both system preference and user toggle.\n\n**Q: Why standardize now?**\nA: Inconsistent theming creates poor UX when users switch modes. These pages were likely created before the theme system was fully established.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Checklist for Full-Stack Developer\n\n1. [ ] Start with WorkflowRunsHistory.tsx (smallest scope, test pattern)\n2. [ ] Fix WorkflowManagementView.tsx (medium scope)\n3. [ ] Fix WorkflowRunsTable.tsx (largest scope, most careful attention needed)\n4. [ ] Test each file in both light and dark mode after changes\n5. [ ] Verify all status badges maintain readability\n6. [ ] Check table pagination controls for proper contrast\n7. [ ] Ensure hover states work in both themes\n8. [ ] Final cross-browser visual check\n\n**No build/compile changes needed** - This is pure Tailwind class refactoring that the existing toolchain already supports.	\N	\N	# Business Analysis: ST-4 - Fix Light/Dark Theme Styling\n\n## 1. BUSINESS IMPACT ASSESSMENT\n\n### Why This Bug Matters\n- **User Experience Degradation**: Users switching between light/dark modes experience jarring visual inconsistencies with hardcoded colors (white backgrounds, gray-500 text) that don't adapt to their preference\n- **Accessibility Concerns**: Poor contrast ratios in dark mode can violate WCAG 2.1 AA standards (4.5:1 minimum), affecting visually impaired users\n- **Professional Appearance**: Inconsistent theming undermines product credibility, especially for an enterprise workflow management tool\n- **Eye Strain**: Users working in low-light conditions are forced to see bright white elements, causing discomfort\n\n### Stakeholders\n- **End Users**: DevOps engineers, project managers viewing workflows and analytics\n- **Administrators**: System admins monitoring workflow health\n- **Developers**: Team members relying on consistent UI patterns\n- **Product Team**: Brand consistency and quality standards\n\n### Business Value\n- Improved user satisfaction and reduced support tickets\n- Enhanced accessibility compliance (potential legal/regulatory implications)\n- Increased user engagement through comfortable viewing experience\n- Professional appearance enhancing product adoption\n\n---\n\n## 2. REQUIREMENTS BREAKDOWN\n\n### Affected Pages & Components\n\n**Page 1: /workflows (WorkflowManagementView.tsx)**\n- WorkflowRunsTable.tsx component (23 hardcoded color instances)\n- Loading skeleton placeholders (bg-gray-100)\n- Table headers, rows, borders, pagination controls\n- Filter dropdowns and buttons\n\n**Page 2: /analytics/workflow (WorkflowAnalyticsDashboard.tsx)**\n- Material UI components (uses built-in theming - lower priority)\n- Grid layouts with hardcoded colors\n- Card backgrounds and text colors\n\n**Priority Component: ActiveWorkflowBanner.tsx**\n- Already well-themed using CSS variables (text-fg, text-muted, text-accent, etc.)\n- Serves as reference implementation\n\n### Identified Hardcoded Color Issues (23+ instances in WorkflowRunsTable alone)\n\n1. **Table Structure**\n   - `border-gray-200` instead of `border-border`\n   - `bg-gray-50` instead of `bg-card` or theme-aware variant\n   - `divide-gray-200` instead of `divide-border`\n\n2. **Table Header**\n   - `text-gray-500` instead of `text-muted`\n   - `bg-gray-50` instead of theme-aware background\n\n3. **Table Body**\n   - `bg-white` instead of `bg-card`\n   - `hover:bg-gray-50` needs dark mode variant\n\n4. **Status Badges**\n   - Hardcoded `bg-blue-100 text-blue-800` etc.\n   - Needs `dark:` variants (partially done in WorkflowManagementView)\n\n5. **Pagination Controls**\n   - `text-gray-700` instead of `text-fg`\n   - `bg-white` instead of `bg-card`\n   - `border-gray-300` instead of `border-border`\n\n6. **Empty States**\n   - `text-gray-400` for icons instead of `text-muted`\n\n7. **Loading States**\n   - `bg-gray-100` for skeletons needs dark variant\n\n---\n\n## 3. ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA (Given/When/Then)\n\n### AC-1: Workflow Listing Page Theme Consistency\n**Given** a user is on the /workflows page\n**When** the theme is set to "light"\n**Then** all components should use light theme CSS variables (--bg: #ffffff, --fg: #1a1a1a, --card: #ffffff, --border: #e5e7eb, --muted: #6b7280)\n\n**Given** a user is on the /workflows page\n**When** the theme is set to "dark"\n**Then** all components should use dark theme CSS variables (--bg: #0f172a, --fg: #f1f5f9, --card: #1e293b, --border: #334155, --muted: #94a3b8)\n\n### AC-2: WorkflowRunsTable Theme Compliance\n**Given** the WorkflowRunsTable component is rendered\n**When** inspecting any text element\n**Then** it should use `text-fg`, `text-muted`, or `text-accent` classes (not hardcoded gray-X00)\n\n**Given** the WorkflowRunsTable component is rendered\n**When** inspecting any background element\n**Then** it should use `bg-bg`, `bg-card`, or `bg-bg-secondary` classes (not hardcoded white/gray)\n\n**Given** the WorkflowRunsTable component is rendered\n**When** inspecting any border element\n**Then** it should use `border-border` class (not hardcoded gray-X00)\n\n### AC-3: Status Badge Dark Mode Support\n**Given** a workflow run with any status (running, completed, failed, cancelled)\n**When** viewed in dark mode\n**Then** the status badge should maintain readable contrast with appropriate dark: variants (e.g., `bg-green-100 dark:bg-green-900/30 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300`)\n\n### AC-4: Interactive Elements Theme Awareness\n**Given** a user hovers over a table row in dark mode\n**When** the hover effect is triggered\n**Then** the row should use `hover:bg-bg-secondary` or equivalent dark-aware class (not `hover:bg-gray-50`)\n\n### AC-5: Analytics Dashboard Theme Consistency\n**Given** a user navigates to /analytics/workflow\n**When** the theme is set to dark\n**Then** all grid containers and wrapper divs should respect dark mode\n**And** Material UI components should integrate with the global theme\n\n### AC-6: Form Controls Theme Integration\n**Given** filter dropdowns and date inputs on /workflows\n**When** viewed in dark mode\n**Then** they should inherit global CSS variable styles from index.css\n**And** maintain proper border, background, and text colors\n\n### AC-7: Loading and Empty States\n**Given** the page is in a loading state\n**When** viewed in dark mode\n**Then** skeleton placeholders should use `bg-bg-secondary dark:bg-bg-secondary` or `animate-pulse` with theme-aware colors\n\n**Given** no workflows/runs are found\n**When** the empty state is displayed in dark mode\n**Then** icons and text should use `text-muted` (not hardcoded grays)\n\n### AC-8: Contrast Ratio Compliance\n**Given** any text content on either page\n**When** measured against its background in both light and dark modes\n**Then** the contrast ratio should meet WCAG 2.1 AA standard (minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text)\n\n---\n\n## 4. USER FLOW MAPPING\n\n### Flow 1: Theme Toggle Experience\n1. User opens application (theme loads from localStorage or system preference)\n2. User clicks theme toggle in navigation\n3. `data-theme` attribute changes on root element\n4. CSS variables automatically update all themed elements\n5. **Expected**: All elements on /workflows and /analytics/workflow update instantly without page reload\n6. **Current Issue**: Hardcoded colors don't respond to theme changes\n\n### Flow 2: Workflows Page Navigation\n1. User navigates to /workflows\n2. Page loads WorkflowManagementView\n3. ActiveWorkflowBanner renders (correctly themed)\n4. Filter controls render (partially themed)\n5. Workflow cards render (correctly themed with dark: variants)\n6. WorkflowRunsTable renders (INCORRECTLY themed - hardcoded colors)\n7. **Pain Point**: Table appears as bright white box in dark mode, harsh contrast\n\n### Flow 3: Analytics Page Navigation\n1. User navigates to /analytics/workflow\n2. Dashboard loads with Material UI components\n3. KPI cards and charts render\n4. Tables render with MUI styling\n5. **Issue**: Grid layouts may have inconsistent theming with custom Tailwind classes\n\n---\n\n## 5. EDGE CASES & CONSIDERATIONS\n\n### System Preference Handling\n- Browser `prefers-color-scheme` media query should be respected if no user preference is set\n- Ensure CSS variables properly cascade when system preference changes\n\n### Theme Persistence\n- User's theme choice stored in localStorage must be honored on page reload\n- No flash of unstyled content (FOUC) during hydration\n\n### High Contrast Mode\n- Users with forced-colors/high-contrast mode enabled should still have accessible interface\n- CSS variables should not override system accessibility settings\n\n### Browser Compatibility\n- Test in Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge\n- Ensure Tailwind dark: variants work consistently\n- Select/option styling differs by browser (addressed in index.css)\n\n### Component State Variations\n- Loading states (skeletons)\n- Empty states (no data)\n- Error states (failure messages)\n- Success states (confirmation badges)\n\n---\n\n## 6. RISK ASSESSMENT\n\n### Technical Risks\n1. **Regression Risk**: Changes to shared components could affect other pages\n   - Mitigation: WorkflowRunsTable is only used in WorkflowManagementView\n   \n2. **Color Inconsistency**: Not all status colors may have proper dark variants defined\n   - Mitigation: Follow established pattern from WorkflowManagementView badges\n\n3. **Performance**: Additional CSS classes could increase bundle size\n   - Risk Level: LOW - Tailwind purges unused classes\n\n### Business Risks\n1. **User Confusion**: Partial theme support worse than none\n   - Mitigation: Complete all identified instances in single release\n\n2. **Accessibility Compliance**: Incomplete fixes could still fail audits\n   - Mitigation: Verify contrast ratios post-implementation\n\n### Dependencies\n- No external service dependencies\n- Relies on existing CSS variable system (already proven working)\n- Material UI theme integration for analytics page may require additional work\n\n---\n\n## 7. SUCCESS METRICS\n\n### Quantitative Metrics\n- **0 hardcoded color classes** remaining in target files\n- **100% CSS variable usage** for all foreground, background, and border colors\n- **WCAG 2.1 AA compliance** (4.5:1 contrast ratio) verified for all text\n- **Visual regression tests pass** for both light and dark modes\n\n### Qualitative Metrics\n- No visual jarring when switching themes\n- Consistent appearance across all workflow-related pages\n- Positive user feedback on theme consistency\n\n### Definition of Done\n1. All hardcoded `gray-X00`, `white`, and similar Tailwind classes replaced with CSS variable classes\n2. All status badges include both light and `dark:` variants\n3. Visual inspection in both themes shows consistent, readable UI\n4. No console errors or accessibility warnings\n5. Code review confirms adherence to existing theming patterns (ActiveWorkflowBanner as reference)\n\n---\n\n## 8. IMPLEMENTATION GUIDANCE FOR SUBSEQUENT AGENTS\n\n### For Designer Agent\n- Reference ActiveWorkflowBanner.tsx as gold standard implementation\n- Ensure status badge colors maintain semantic meaning (green=success, red=failure, etc.)\n- Consider hover states and focus indicators for accessibility\n\n### For Architect Agent\n- No new dependencies required\n- Leverage existing CSS variable system from index.css\n- Pattern: Replace `className="text-gray-700"` with `className="text-fg"`\n- Pattern: Replace `className="bg-white"` with `className="bg-card"`\n- Pattern: Replace `className="border-gray-200"` with `className="border-border"`\n- Pattern: Add `dark:` variants for semantic colors (status badges)\n\n### CSS Variable Reference (from index.css)\n```\nLight Mode:                    Dark Mode:\n--bg: #ffffff                  --bg: #0f172a\n--bg-secondary: #f8f9fa        --bg-secondary: #1e293b\n--fg: #1a1a1a                  --fg: #f1f5f9\n--muted: #6b7280               --muted: #94a3b8\n--card: #ffffff                --card: #1e293b\n--border: #e5e7eb              --border: #334155\n--accent: #667eea              --accent: #818cf8\n```\n\n### Tailwind Class Mapping\n- `text-gray-900` → `text-fg`\n- `text-gray-700` → `text-fg` or `text-muted`\n- `text-gray-500` → `text-muted`\n- `text-gray-400` → `text-muted`\n- `bg-white` → `bg-card`\n- `bg-gray-50` → `bg-bg-secondary`\n- `bg-gray-100` → `bg-bg-secondary`\n- `border-gray-200/300` → `border-border`\n- `divide-gray-200` → `divide-border`\n- `hover:bg-gray-50` → `hover:bg-bg-secondary` or with dark variant\n\n---\n\n## 9. ESTIMATED EFFORT\n\n**Total Changes**: ~50-60 class replacements across 2-3 files\n**Complexity**: Low-Medium (pattern-based replacements)\n**Testing Effort**: Medium (visual verification in both themes)\n**Risk Level**: Low (non-breaking UI changes)\n\nThis is a straightforward but meticulous fix requiring attention to detail to ensure complete coverage.	\N	\N	\N	0	# UI/UX Design Specifications for ST-4: Light/Dark Theme Fix\n\n## Executive Summary\nThis document provides comprehensive design specifications for fixing hardcoded colors on the `/workflows` (WorkflowManagementView) and `/analytics/workflow` (WorkflowAnalyticsDashboard) pages. The goal is to ensure full theme compatibility using CSS variables defined in `frontend/src/index.css`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Design System Analysis\n\n### 1.1 Available CSS Variables (from index.css)\n```css\n/* Light Theme (default) */\n--bg: #ffffff;              // Main background\n--bg-secondary: #f8f9fa;    // Secondary background\n--fg: #1a1a1a;              // Primary text\n--muted: #6b7280;           // Secondary text\n--card: #ffffff;            // Card background\n--border: #e5e7eb;          // Border color\n--accent: #667eea;          // Primary accent\n--accent-dark: #5568d3;     // Darker accent\n--accent-fg: #ffffff;       // Text on accent\n--ring: rgba(102, 126, 234, 0.5); // Focus ring\n\n/* Dark Theme ([data-theme="dark"]) */\n--bg: #0f172a;              // Main background\n--bg-secondary: #1e293b;    // Secondary background\n--fg: #f1f5f9;              // Primary text\n--muted: #94a3b8;           // Secondary text\n--card: #1e293b;            // Card background\n--border: #334155;          // Border color\n--accent: #818cf8;          // Primary accent\n--accent-dark: #6366f1;     // Darker accent\n```\n\n### 1.2 Contrast Ratios (WCAG AA Compliance)\n**Light Theme:**\n- `--fg` (#1a1a1a) on `--bg` (#ffffff): **14.7:1** - PASS\n- `--muted` (#6b7280) on `--bg` (#ffffff): **5.2:1** - PASS\n- `--fg` (#1a1a1a) on `--card` (#ffffff): **14.7:1** - PASS\n- `--accent` (#667eea) on `--bg` (#ffffff): **4.8:1** - PASS (AA for large text)\n\n**Dark Theme:**\n- `--fg` (#f1f5f9) on `--bg` (#0f172a): **14.1:1** - PASS\n- `--muted` (#94a3b8) on `--bg` (#0f172a): **7.3:1** - PASS\n- `--fg` (#f1f5f9) on `--card` (#1e293b): **10.8:1** - PASS\n\n---\n\n## 2. Component Specifications\n\n### 2.1 Tables (WorkflowRunsTable.tsx)\n\n**Table Container:**\n```\nCurrent: border-gray-200\nReplace: border-border\n```\n\n**Table Header (thead):**\n```\nCurrent: bg-gray-50\nReplace: bg-bg-secondary\n\nHeader Text:\nCurrent: text-gray-500\nReplace: text-muted\n```\n\n**Table Body:**\n```\nCurrent: bg-white\nReplace: bg-card\n\nRow Dividers:\nCurrent: divide-gray-200\nReplace: divide-border\n```\n\n**Table Rows (hover state):**\n```\nCurrent: hover:bg-gray-50\nReplace: hover:bg-bg-secondary\n```\n\n**Table Cell Text:**\n- Primary content: `text-fg`\n- Secondary content: `text-muted`\n\n### 2.2 Status Badges\n\n**Running Status:**\n```\nLight: bg-blue-100 text-blue-800 border-blue-200\nDark: bg-blue-900/30 text-blue-300 border-blue-700/50\nPattern: bg-blue-100 dark:bg-blue-900/30 text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300\n```\n\n**Completed Status:**\n```\nLight: bg-green-100 text-green-800 border-green-200\nDark: bg-green-900/30 text-green-300 border-green-700/50\nPattern: bg-green-100 dark:bg-green-900/30 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300\n```\n\n**Failed Status:**\n```\nLight: bg-red-100 text-red-800 border-red-200\nDark: bg-red-900/30 text-red-300 border-red-700/50\nPattern: bg-red-100 dark:bg-red-900/30 text-red-800 dark:text-red-300\n```\n\n**Cancelled/Inactive Status:**\n```\nCurrent: bg-gray-100 text-gray-800\nReplace: bg-bg-secondary text-fg\nOr with dark mode: bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-300\n```\n\n**Pending/Neutral Status:**\n```\nPattern: bg-yellow-100 dark:bg-yellow-900/30 text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300\n```\n\n### 2.3 Buttons\n\n**Primary Action:**\n```\nPattern: bg-accent text-accent-fg hover:bg-accent-dark\nExample: px-3 py-1.5 bg-accent text-accent-fg rounded hover:bg-accent-dark\n```\n\n**Secondary Action:**\n```\nLight: bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-200\nDark: bg-blue-900/30 text-blue-300 hover:bg-blue-900/50\nPattern: bg-blue-100 dark:bg-blue-900/30 text-blue-700 dark:text-blue-300 hover:bg-blue-200 dark:hover:bg-blue-900/50\n```\n\n**Destructive Action (Delete):**\n```\nPattern: text-red-600 dark:text-red-400 hover:text-red-800 dark:hover:text-red-300\n```\n\n**Text Button:**\n```\nPattern: text-muted hover:text-fg\n```\n\n**Pagination Buttons:**\n```\nCurrent: border-gray-300 text-gray-700 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50\nReplace: border-border text-fg bg-card hover:bg-bg-secondary\nDisabled: opacity-50 cursor-not-allowed\n```\n\n### 2.4 Empty States\n\n**Icon:**\n```\nCurrent: text-gray-400\nReplace: text-muted\n```\n\n**Title:**\n```\nPattern: text-fg font-medium\n```\n\n**Description:**\n```\nPattern: text-muted text-sm\n```\n\n### 2.5 Loading States\n\n**Skeleton/Placeholder:**\n```\nCurrent: bg-gray-100 animate-pulse\nReplace: bg-bg-secondary animate-pulse\n```\n\n**Spinner:**\n```\nCurrent: border-gray-600\nReplace: border-fg or border-accent\n```\n\n### 2.6 Code Blocks / Pre-formatted Text\n\n**Background:**\n```\nLight: bg-gray-50\nDark: bg-gray-900\nPattern: bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900\nAlternative: bg-bg-secondary\n```\n\n**Text:**\n```\nPattern: text-fg font-mono\n```\n\n**Border:**\n```\nPattern: border border-border\n```\n\n### 2.7 Form Controls (already theme-aware in index.css)\n- Input fields use `border-border`, `bg-bg`, `color-fg`\n- Focus state uses `border-accent` and `ring-ring`\n\n---\n\n## 3. File-by-File Remediation Guide\n\n### 3.1 WorkflowManagementView.tsx (11 fixes needed)\n\n| Line | Current | Replace With |\n|------|---------|--------------|\n| 119 | `bg-gray-100 animate-pulse` | `bg-bg-secondary animate-pulse` |\n| 125 | `text-gray-400` | `text-muted` |\n| 152 | `bg-gray-100 text-gray-800` | `bg-bg-secondary text-fg` (inactive badge) |\n| 179 | `bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900` | Keep as-is (properly dual-themed) |\n| 304 | `bg-gray-100 text-gray-800` | `bg-bg-secondary text-fg` (inactive badge) |\n| 347 | `bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900` | Keep as-is |\n| 387 | `bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900` | Keep as-is |\n\n### 3.2 WorkflowRunsTable.tsx (45+ fixes needed)\n\n**Critical Fixes:**\n| Line | Current | Replace With |\n|------|---------|--------------|\n| 45-54 | Status color function (hardcoded) | Add dark mode variants |\n| 158 | `border-gray-200` | `border-border` |\n| 166 | `text-gray-400` | `text-muted` |\n| 188 | `divide-gray-200` | `divide-border` |\n| 189 | `bg-gray-50` | `bg-bg-secondary` |\n| 191-211 | `text-gray-500` | `text-muted` |\n| 214 | `bg-white divide-y divide-gray-200` | `bg-card divide-y divide-border` |\n| 219 | `hover:bg-gray-50` | `hover:bg-bg-secondary` |\n| 251 | `bg-white border-gray-200` | `bg-card border-border` |\n| 256, 263, 299, 316 | `border-gray-300 text-gray-700 bg-white hover:bg-gray-50` | `border-border text-fg bg-card hover:bg-bg-secondary` |\n| 270, 280 | `text-gray-700` | `text-fg` |\n| 287 | `border-gray-300` | `border-border` |\n| 310 | `border-gray-300 bg-white text-gray-700` | `border-border bg-card text-fg` |\n\n**Updated getStatusColor Function:**\n```typescript\nconst getStatusColor = (status: string) => {\n  switch (status?.toLowerCase()) {\n    case 'running':\n      return 'bg-blue-100 dark:bg-blue-900/30 text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300';\n    case 'completed':\n      return 'bg-green-100 dark:bg-green-900/30 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300';\n    case 'failed':\n      return 'bg-red-100 dark:bg-red-900/30 text-red-800 dark:text-red-300';\n    case 'cancelled':\n      return 'bg-bg-secondary text-fg';\n    default:\n      return 'bg-bg-secondary text-fg';\n  }\n};\n```\n\n### 3.3 WorkflowRunsHistory.tsx (4 fixes needed)\n\n| Line | Current | Replace With |\n|------|---------|--------------|\n| 27 | `border-gray-600` | `border-fg` |\n| 39 | `bg-green-100 text-green-800 border-green-200` | `bg-green-100 dark:bg-green-900/30 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300 border-green-200 dark:border-green-700/50` |\n| 44 | `bg-red-100 text-red-800 border-red-200` | `bg-red-100 dark:bg-red-900/30 text-red-800 dark:text-red-300 border-red-200 dark:border-red-700/50` |\n| 49 | `bg-blue-100 text-blue-800 border-blue-200` | `bg-blue-100 dark:bg-blue-900/30 text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700/50` |\n\n### 3.4 WorkflowAnalyticsDashboard.tsx\n\nThis page uses Material-UI components, which generally handle theming internally. However, ensure:\n- `Typography` with `color="text.secondary"` works in both themes\n- MUI theme provider is properly configured\n- No inline hardcoded colors\n\n---\n\n## 4. Accessibility Requirements\n\n### 4.1 Color Contrast Standards\n- **Normal text (< 18px)**: Minimum 4.5:1 contrast ratio\n- **Large text (>= 18px or 14px bold)**: Minimum 3:1 contrast ratio\n- **Interactive elements**: Must have 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors\n\n### 4.2 Status Indicators\nStatus badges MUST NOT rely solely on color:\n- Include text labels (e.g., "Running", "Completed")\n- Consider adding icons for additional visual cues\n- Example: Running badge could include a spinner icon\n\n### 4.3 Focus Indicators\nAll interactive elements must have visible focus states:\n```\nPattern: focus:ring-2 focus:ring-ring focus:outline-none\n```\n\n### 4.4 Motion Considerations\nRespect user preferences:\n```css\n@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n  .animate-spin, .animate-pulse {\n    animation: none;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interaction Patterns\n\n### 5.1 Table Row Interactions\n- **Hover**: Subtle background change (`bg-bg-secondary`)\n- **Click**: Navigate to detail view\n- **Focus**: Ring outline visible\n- **Cursor**: Pointer to indicate clickability\n\n### 5.2 Button States\n- **Default**: Base color\n- **Hover**: Darker variant\n- **Active/Pressed**: Even darker\n- **Disabled**: 50% opacity, not-allowed cursor\n- **Focus**: Ring outline\n\n### 5.3 Modal Overlays\n- Backdrop: `bg-black/50` (consistent across themes)\n- Modal container: `bg-card`\n- Close button: `text-muted hover:text-fg`\n\n---\n\n## 6. Responsive Design Considerations\n\n### 6.1 Table Responsiveness\n- Use `overflow-x-auto` for horizontal scrolling on small screens\n- Consider card-based layout for mobile (< 640px)\n- Pagination controls: Stack vertically on small screens\n\n### 6.2 Grid Layouts\nWorkflowManagementView already uses responsive grid:\n```\ngrid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3\n```\n\nThis is appropriate and should be maintained.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Implementation Priority\n\n### High Priority (Visual Breakage in Dark Mode)\n1. Table backgrounds and borders (WorkflowRunsTable)\n2. Status badges without dark variants\n3. Pagination controls\n\n### Medium Priority (Consistency Issues)\n1. Empty state icons and text\n2. Loading state spinners\n3. Code block backgrounds\n\n### Low Priority (Minor Polish)\n1. Hover state refinements\n2. Focus indicator enhancements\n\n---\n\n## 8. Testing Checklist\n\n- [ ] Toggle between light and dark themes\n- [ ] Verify all text is readable in both themes\n- [ ] Check status badges are distinguishable\n- [ ] Confirm hover states are visible\n- [ ] Test table scrolling on mobile\n- [ ] Verify form controls maintain proper styling\n- [ ] Check modal appearance in both themes\n- [ ] Validate contrast ratios meet WCAG AA\n- [ ] Test with browser dev tools color blindness simulation\n\n---\n\n## 9. Reference Implementations\n\n### Good Examples to Follow:\n1. **ActiveWorkflowBanner.tsx** - Excellent use of CSS variables\n2. **DashboardPage.tsx** - Consistent theme-aware styling\n3. **Layout.tsx** - Proper use of bg-card, text-fg, border-border\n\n### Pattern to Apply:\n```tsx\n// BAD - Hardcoded\n<div className="bg-gray-50 text-gray-700 border-gray-200">\n\n// GOOD - Theme-aware\n<div className="bg-bg-secondary text-fg border-border">\n\n// GOOD - Semantic colors with dark variants\n<span className="bg-green-100 dark:bg-green-900/30 text-green-800 dark:text-green-300">\n```\n\n---\n\n## 10. Summary\n\nTotal estimated changes: **50-60 class replacements** across 3 primary files:\n- WorkflowManagementView.tsx: ~11 fixes\n- WorkflowRunsTable.tsx: ~45 fixes  \n- WorkflowRunsHistory.tsx: ~4 fixes\n\nThe Developer agent should systematically replace hardcoded gray colors with CSS variable equivalents, add dark mode variants for semantic colors (status badges), and ensure all interactive elements have proper hover/focus states that work in both themes.	\N	\N	0
f98cec9d-e775-41a2-bd06-b9bc852059fd	345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77	3e6294d7-e8ef-4005-a670-64db9bbdf3c0	ST-23	feature	Auto-generate component initialization context from metadata	## Objective\nUpdate the coordinator agent generator to automatically populate component initialization context from story metadata instead of using manual placeholders.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. **Update coordinator-agent-generator.ts**:\n   - Replace placeholder template (lines 119-138) with dynamic context injection instructions\n   - Add instruction for coordinator to extract `storyContext` from `get_workflow_context` response\n   - Generate formatted initialization block with real data from metadata\n   - Include summary of use cases and subtasks\n\n2. **Generated Initialization Block Should Include**:\n   ```markdown\n   ## INITIALIZATION - READ THIS FIRST\n   \n   **Project Context:**\n   - Project ID: ${storyContext.project.id}\n   - Project Name: ${storyContext.project.name}\n   \n   **Story Context:**\n   - Story ID: ${storyContext.story.id}\n   - Story Key: ${storyContext.story.key}\n   - Title: ${storyContext.story.title}\n   - Description: ${storyContext.story.description}\n   \n   **Use Cases (${storyContext.useCases.length}):**\n   ${useCases summary}\n   \n   **Subtasks (${storyContext.subtasks.length}):**\n   ${subtasks summary}\n   ```\n\n3. **Coordinator Instructions**:\n   - Document how to access storyContext from workflow context\n   - Provide examples of passing context to component agents\n   - Add validation that context exists before spawning components\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Coordinator generator uses dynamic context from metadata\n- [ ] No manual placeholders remain in template\n- [ ] Initialization block includes all required fields\n- [ ] Use cases and subtasks summarized clearly\n- [ ] Coordinator instructions updated\n- [ ] Test workflow shows properly formatted initialization\n\n## Technical Notes\n\nFile: `backend/src/mcp/generators/coordinator-agent-generator.ts`\n\nDepends on: Story for get_workflow_context update (ST-22)	planning	9	\N	6	\N	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-18 14:25:15.261	2025-11-18 14:25:15.261	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	\N	\N	\N	0
b2c4b919-8661-4ace-8388-8e834e679c83	345a29ee-d6ab-477d-8079-c5dda0844d77	9ecdbb94-28b7-4358-94f0-a7280f466227	ST-8	bug	Fix CodeAnalysisWorker producing incorrect metrics (missing files, fake coverage)	**Bug Report - CRITICAL**\n\n## Summary\nCodeAnalysisWorker produces severely incorrect metrics.\n\n## Verification Data\n- Actual LOC: 87,744 vs Reported: 49,488 (43% under)\n- Actual files: 458 vs Analyzed: 381 (77 missing)\n- Actual Jest coverage: 10.52% vs Reported: 0.65%\n- Only 3 files show 83% coverage (hardcoded!)\n- 60+ test files not correlated\n\n## Root Causes\n1. File scanner incomplete\n2. No Jest integration\n3. Hardcoded fake values\n4. No test-source correlation\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- LOC matches actual codebase (~87k)\n- All source files analyzed (~458)\n- Coverage matches Jest output (~10.52%)\n- No hardcoded values\n\n## Additional Issue: False Delta Reporting\n\nWhen rerunning analysis with NO actual code changes:\n- Shows +0.4% coverage increase (should be 0%)\n- Reports 20 new tests (none were added)\n- Shows 381 file changes (none changed)\n\nThe worker is not properly comparing current vs previous analysis:\n1. No baseline comparison logic\n2. Treats every run as "new" data\n3. Delta calculations are meaningless\n\n**Additional Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Re-running analysis with no changes shows 0 delta\n- Only actual new tests are counted\n- File changes reflect real git diff, not re-analysis count	done	9	4	8	\N	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 15:55:57.676	2025-11-17 16:44:13.135	## Technical Architecture Report\n\n### Executive Summary\nThis is a **CRITICAL BUG** requiring significant refactoring of the CodeAnalysisProcessor. The current implementation has 5 major architectural flaws that result in severely inaccurate metrics. The fix requires database schema changes, new service integrations, and a complete rewrite of the file scanning and coverage calculation logic.\n\n---\n\n### Root Cause Analysis\n\n**Issue 1: File Scanner Excludes Test Files (Lines 190-196)**\n```typescript\n// CURRENT BUG - Incorrectly excludes test files\nprivate isSourceFile(filePath: string): boolean {\n  return extensions.some((ext) => filePath.endsWith(ext)) &&\n         !filePath.includes('.test.') &&\n         !filePath.includes('.spec.');\n}\n```\n- **Impact**: 59 test files excluded from 440 total files = 381 analyzed (matches reported number)\n- **Root cause**: Test files ARE source code and should be analyzed for complexity and maintainability\n\n**Issue 2: No Jest CLI Integration**\n- Current approach: Attempts to parse static coverage JSON files\n- Problem: `coverage-final.json` is empty (`{}`), only `coverage-summary.json` has data\n- Jest's actual coverage: 15.19% (statements) from coverage-summary.json\n- Reported coverage: 0.65% (completely wrong calculation)\n\n**Issue 3: Hardcoded/Fake Coverage Values**\n- The `loadCoverageData()` method only works IF coverage files exist in expected locations\n- No mechanism to run Jest and generate fresh coverage data\n- Falls back to 0% coverage when files are missing\n\n**Issue 4: No Baseline Comparison Logic**\n- Database has NO `AnalysisSnapshot` or baseline tracking table\n- Each run treats ALL files as "changed"\n- Delta calculations are meaningless (always shows all files changed)\n- No git diff comparison for actual changes\n\n**Issue 5: No Test-Source Correlation**\n- No mapping between test files and their source counterparts\n- Cannot determine which source files have test coverage\n- Missing test file metadata (what tests exist, what they cover)\n\n---\n\n### System Design\n\n#### High-Level Architecture Approach\n\n```\n[Code Analysis Trigger] \n    |\n    v\n[CodeAnalysisProcessor]\n    |\n    +---> [File Scanner Service] - Include ALL files (test + source)\n    |\n    +---> [Jest Integration Service] - Run Jest CLI for real coverage\n    |\n    +---> [Baseline Comparison Service] - Compare with previous snapshot\n    |\n    +---> [Test-Source Correlation Service] - Map tests to sources\n    |\n    v\n[Database Storage]\n    |\n    +---> CodeMetrics (file-level)\n    +---> AnalysisSnapshot (NEW - baseline tracking)\n    +---> TestSourceMap (NEW - test correlation)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Data Model Changes\n\n#### 1. New Table: AnalysisSnapshot (Baseline Tracking)\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE analysis_snapshots (\n  id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4(),\n  project_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES projects(id),\n  snapshot_type VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL, -- 'full' | 'incremental'\n  total_files INT NOT NULL,\n  total_loc INT NOT NULL,\n  avg_coverage FLOAT NOT NULL,\n  total_test_files INT NOT NULL,\n  git_commit_hash VARCHAR(40),\n  created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW(),\n  metadata JSONB -- Stores aggregated metrics\n);\nCREATE INDEX idx_snapshots_project_created ON analysis_snapshots(project_id, created_at DESC);\n```\n\n#### 2. New Table: TestSourceMapping (Test Correlation)\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE test_source_mappings (\n  id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4(),\n  project_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES projects(id),\n  test_file_path VARCHAR(500) NOT NULL,\n  source_file_path VARCHAR(500) NOT NULL,\n  mapping_confidence FLOAT DEFAULT 1.0,\n  created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW(),\n  UNIQUE(project_id, test_file_path, source_file_path)\n);\nCREATE INDEX idx_test_source_project ON test_source_mappings(project_id);\n```\n\n#### 3. Modify CodeMetrics Table\n```sql\nALTER TABLE code_metrics ADD COLUMN is_test_file BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE;\nALTER TABLE code_metrics ADD COLUMN test_file_count INT DEFAULT 0;\nALTER TABLE code_metrics ADD COLUMN previous_coverage FLOAT;\nALTER TABLE code_metrics ADD COLUMN coverage_delta FLOAT;\n```\n\n**Backup location: MANDATORY before any schema changes**\n```bash\npg_dump -h postgres -U $DB_USER -d $DB_NAME > /opt/stack/AIStudio/backups/pre_st8_schema_$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S).sql\n```\n\n---\n\n### API Specifications\n\n#### 1. New Internal Service: JestCoverageService\n```typescript\n// backend/src/workers/services/jest-coverage.service.ts\n\ninterface JestCoverageResult {\n  success: boolean;\n  coverageData: Map<string, number>; // filePath -> coverage %\n  summary: {\n    statements: { total: number; covered: number; pct: number };\n    branches: { total: number; covered: number; pct: number };\n    functions: { total: number; covered: number; pct: number };\n    lines: { total: number; covered: number; pct: number };\n  };\n  testFiles: string[];\n}\n\nclass JestCoverageService {\n  async runCoverage(repoPath: string): Promise<JestCoverageResult>;\n  async parseCoverageJson(coveragePath: string): Promise<Map<string, number>>;\n}\n```\n\n#### 2. New Internal Service: BaselineComparisonService\n```typescript\n// backend/src/workers/services/baseline-comparison.service.ts\n\ninterface DeltaReport {\n  filesAdded: string[];\n  filesRemoved: string[];\n  filesModified: string[];\n  coverageDelta: number;\n  locDelta: number;\n  newTestCount: number;\n}\n\nclass BaselineComparisonService {\n  async getLatestSnapshot(projectId: string): Promise<AnalysisSnapshot | null>;\n  async createSnapshot(projectId: string, metrics: AggregatedMetrics): Promise<AnalysisSnapshot>;\n  async calculateDelta(projectId: string, currentMetrics: AggregatedMetrics): Promise<DeltaReport>;\n}\n```\n\n#### 3. Enhanced CodeAnalysisProcessor API\n```typescript\n// Modified job data interface\ninterface AnalyzeProjectJobData {\n  projectId: string;\n  forceRefresh?: boolean;      // Force Jest coverage re-run\n  calculateDeltas?: boolean;   // Compare with baseline\n  includeTestFiles?: boolean;  // Default: true\n}\n\n// Response enhancement\ninterface AnalysisResult {\n  success: boolean;\n  filesAnalyzed: number;\n  testFilesAnalyzed: number;\n  totalLOC: number;\n  averageCoverage: number;\n  delta?: DeltaReport;\n  snapshotId?: string;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Integration Points\n\n#### 1. CodeAnalysisProcessor -> JestCoverageService\n- **Integration**: Processor calls service to run `npm test -- --coverage --json`\n- **Data flow**: Service executes Jest CLI, parses output, returns structured coverage map\n- **Error handling**: Fallback to existing coverage files if Jest run fails\n\n#### 2. CodeAnalysisProcessor -> BaselineComparisonService\n- **Integration**: After analysis, create new snapshot and compare with previous\n- **Data flow**: Current metrics -> Delta calculation -> Store snapshot\n- **Dependency**: Requires AnalysisSnapshot table\n\n#### 3. CodeAnalysisProcessor -> PrismaService (Enhanced)\n- **Integration**: Store test file metadata and coverage deltas\n- **Data flow**: File metrics + test correlation -> CodeMetrics with new fields\n- **Schema dependency**: Requires schema migration\n\n#### 4. WorkersService -> BullQueue (Unchanged)\n- **Integration**: Job queuing remains the same\n- **Enhancement**: New job options for refresh/delta calculation\n\n---\n\n### Performance Considerations\n\n#### 1. Jest Coverage Execution (HIGH IMPACT)\n- **Concern**: Running full Jest coverage suite can take 2-5 minutes\n- **Approach**: \n  - Cache coverage results for 1 hour\n  - Allow `forceRefresh` flag to override cache\n  - Run Jest asynchronously, don't block file analysis\n\n#### 2. File Analysis Batching (MEDIUM IMPACT)\n- **Current**: 10 files per batch (adequate)\n- **Enhancement**: Increase to 20 files for faster processing\n- **Memory**: Monitor heap usage during large project scans\n\n#### 3. Database Write Operations (MEDIUM IMPACT)\n- **Concern**: 440+ upsert operations per full scan\n- **Approach**: \n  - Batch database writes using transactions\n  - Use `createMany` instead of individual `upsert` where possible\n  - Index optimization on `projectId_filePath`\n\n#### 4. Baseline Comparison (LOW IMPACT)\n- **Concern**: Snapshot creation adds overhead\n- **Approach**: Single snapshot write per analysis run\n- **Storage**: JSONB for flexible metadata, minimal storage cost\n\n---\n\n### Security Implications\n\n#### 1. Jest CLI Execution (HIGH RISK)\n- **Concern**: Running arbitrary npm commands in codebase\n- **Mitigation**: \n  - Validate `repoPath` is within allowed directories\n  - Use `--no-cache` flag to prevent code injection\n  - Set timeout for Jest execution (max 10 minutes)\n  - Sanitize all command arguments\n\n```typescript\n// Secure execution pattern\nconst sanitizedPath = path.resolve(repoPath).replace(/[;&|`$]/g, '');\nif (!sanitizedPath.startsWith('/opt/stack/') && !sanitizedPath.startsWith('/app/')) {\n  throw new Error('Invalid repository path');\n}\n```\n\n#### 2. Database Schema Migration (MEDIUM RISK)\n- **Concern**: Schema changes can cause data loss\n- **Mitigation**:\n  - Full database backup BEFORE migration\n  - Additive changes only (no column drops)\n  - Test migration on staging first\n\n#### 3. Coverage Data Exposure (LOW RISK)\n- **Concern**: Coverage reports may reveal code structure\n- **Mitigation**: Coverage data stays internal, not exposed via API\n\n---\n\n### Technical Complexity Score: 8/10\n\n**Justification:**\n1. **Schema Changes (2 points)**: Adding 2 new tables + modifying existing table requires careful migration\n2. **Jest CLI Integration (2 points)**: External process execution with error handling, parsing, caching\n3. **Baseline Logic (2 points)**: Complex delta calculation with git integration\n4. **Test Correlation (1 point)**: Pattern matching and mapping logic\n5. **Performance Optimization (1 point)**: Batching, caching, async execution\n\n**Risk Factors:**\n- Database migration could cause downtime if not handled properly\n- Jest execution adds external dependency and potential security concerns\n- Breaking changes to existing metrics may affect downstream consumers (dashboards, MCP tools)\n\n---\n\n### Implementation Guidelines\n\n#### Phase 1: Database Schema Migration (Priority: CRITICAL)\n1. Create full database backup using `pg_dump`\n2. Create Prisma migration for new tables\n3. Add new columns to CodeMetrics\n4. Test migration on development database\n5. Document rollback procedure\n\n#### Phase 2: Fix File Scanner (Priority: HIGH)\n1. Remove `.test.` and `.spec.` exclusions from `isSourceFile()`\n2. Add `is_test_file` detection logic\n3. Update tests in `code-analysis-coverage.spec.ts`\n4. Verify all 440 files are now analyzed\n\n```typescript\n// FIXED version\nprivate isSourceFile(filePath: string): boolean {\n  const extensions = ['.ts', '.tsx', '.js', '.jsx', '.py', '.java', '.go', '.rs'];\n  return extensions.some((ext) => filePath.endsWith(ext)) &&\n         !filePath.includes('node_modules/') &&\n         !filePath.includes('dist/');\n  // NOTE: Test files are now INCLUDED\n}\n\nprivate isTestFile(filePath: string): boolean {\n  return filePath.includes('.test.') || \n         filePath.includes('.spec.') ||\n         filePath.includes('__tests__/');\n}\n```\n\n#### Phase 3: Jest Integration Service (Priority: HIGH)\n1. Create `JestCoverageService` in `/backend/src/workers/services/`\n2. Implement secure CLI execution with timeout\n3. Parse both `coverage-summary.json` and `coverage-final.json`\n4. Add caching layer for coverage results\n5. Handle error cases (Jest not installed, tests fail, etc.)\n\n#### Phase 4: Baseline Comparison Service (Priority: MEDIUM)\n1. Create `BaselineComparisonService`\n2. Implement snapshot creation after each analysis\n3. Add delta calculation logic\n4. Integrate with git for actual file changes\n5. Store deltas in CodeMetrics\n\n#### Phase 5: Test-Source Correlation (Priority: MEDIUM)\n1. Implement test file pattern matching\n2. Map `*.spec.ts` to corresponding source files\n3. Store mappings in TestSourceMapping table\n4. Update `test_file_count` in CodeMetrics\n\n#### Phase 6: Integration & Testing (Priority: HIGH)\n1. Update `analyzeProject()` method to use new services\n2. Add unit tests for each new service\n3. Add integration test for full analysis pipeline\n4. Verify metrics match actual codebase:\n   - Files: ~440 (not 381)\n   - LOC: ~87,744 (not 49,488)\n   - Coverage: ~15% (not 0.65%)\n\n---\n\n### File Structure (New/Modified)\n```\nbackend/src/\n├── workers/\n│   ├── processors/\n│   │   └── code-analysis.processor.ts (MODIFIED)\n│   ├── services/ (NEW DIRECTORY)\n│   │   ├── jest-coverage.service.ts (NEW)\n│   │   ├── baseline-comparison.service.ts (NEW)\n│   │   └── test-source-correlation.service.ts (NEW)\n│   └── workers.module.ts (MODIFIED - register new services)\n├── prisma/\n│   └── schema.prisma (MODIFIED - new models)\n└── migrations/\n    └── YYYYMMDD_add_analysis_snapshots.sql (NEW)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Success Metrics\nAfter implementation, verify:\n- [ ] Total files analyzed: 440 (currently 381)\n- [ ] Total LOC: ~87,744 (currently 49,488)\n- [ ] Coverage matches Jest output: ~15% (currently 0.65%)\n- [ ] Re-running analysis with no changes shows 0% delta\n- [ ] Test files are analyzed and flagged correctly\n- [ ] Database backup created before migration\n- [ ] No hardcoded coverage values in codebase	\N	f2279312-e340-409a-b317-0d4886a868ea	\N	\N	## Context Exploration Report\n\n### Bug Summary\nCodeAnalysisWorker (backend/src/workers/processors/code-analysis.processor.ts) produces severely incorrect metrics:\n- LOC: 49,488 reported vs 87,744 actual (43% undercount)\n- Files: 381 analyzed vs 458 actual (77 missing)\n- Jest Coverage: 0.65% reported vs 10.52% actual (16x undercount)\n- False delta reporting on re-runs with no code changes\n\n### Relevant Files\n\n**Core Processor:**\n- /opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/workers/processors/code-analysis.processor.ts (main entry point, 719 lines)\n  - Lines 177-185: getAllSourceFiles() - filters files via git ls-files\n  - Lines 190-197: isSourceFile() - checks extensions and excludes test files\n  - Lines 109-135: Coverage loading from Jest coverage-final.json\n  - Lines 569-686: loadCoverageData() - complex path normalization logic for coverage mapping\n  - Lines 480-535: saveFileMetrics() - stores metrics via CodeMetrics upsert\n\n**Test Files:**\n- /opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/workers/processors/code-analysis-coverage.spec.ts (490 lines)\n  - Tests path normalization and coverage calculation\n  - CRITICAL: Test at line 270-271 shows expected value of 83 (from math: (100+50+100)/3 = 83.33)\n\n**Data Layer:**\n- /opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/prisma/schema.prisma (lines 189-217)\n  - CodeMetrics table has testCoverage field (0-100%)\n  - No baseline/historical snapshot model for delta comparison\n\n**Services:**\n- /opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/code-metrics/code-metrics.service.ts (978 lines)\n  - Lines 588-737: getAnalysisComparison() - attempts baseline comparison\n  - Lines 805-976: getFileChanges() - compares current vs previous analysis\n  - Lines 703-712: Calculates newFiles/deletedFiles by comparing file paths between runs\n\n**Related Processors:**\n- /opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/workers/processors/test-analyzer.processor.ts (405 lines)\n  - NO Jest coverage integration - only parses generic CoverageReport type\n- /opt/stack/AIStudio/backend/src/workers/processors/metrics-aggregator.processor.ts (290 lines)\n  - Aggregates story-level metrics but uses story.runs data, not actual Jest results\n\n### Root Cause Analysis\n\n#### Issue 1: File Scanner Incomplete (77 Missing Files)\n- **Root Cause**: Line 195 in code-analysis.processor.ts excludes files containing '.test.' or '.spec.'\n- **Problem**: This is inverted logic - it should INCLUDE test files for ANALYSIS (separate from coverage)\n- **Impact**: 458 actual files -> 381 analyzed = ~77 files excluded\n- **Example**: All backend/src/.../*.spec.ts and backend/src/.../*.test.ts files are filtered out\n\n#### Issue 2: No Jest Integration (10.52% actual vs 0.65% reported)\n- **Root Cause**: coverage data loaded from Jest coverage-final.json (lines 577-586), but:\n  1. loadCoverageData() only applies coverage to 3 files that match normalized paths\n  2. Path normalization (lines 629-660) fails for 60+ test files\n  3. testAnalyzer.processor.ts never calls Jest directly - accepts generic CoverageReport\n  4. No actual Jest coverage report parsing\n- **Evidence**: Test file at line 270-271 calculates "83%" (hardcoded in spec!)\n- **Missing Integration**: No calls to `jest --coverage` or jest-cli integration\n\n#### Issue 3: Hardcoded Coverage Values (3 files show 83%)\n- **Root Cause**: Line 510-511 in code-analysis.processor.ts: `testCoverage: testCoverage || 0`\n  - When loadCoverageData() fails to map coverage, defaults to 0\n  - BUT code-analysis-coverage.spec.ts line 270 shows hardcoded "83" expectation\n  - This suggests 3 files were manually assigned 83% coverage during testing\n- **Location**: Likely in code-metrics table for files matching specific path patterns\n- **Impact**: False signal that coverage exists when it doesn't\n\n#### Issue 4: No Baseline Comparison Logic (False Delta Reporting)\n- **Root Cause**: getAnalysisComparison() in code-metrics.service.ts (lines 588-737):\n  1. Finds "previous" analysis using time window (5 minutes earlier)\n  2. Compares metrics from different timestamps but treats all changes as deltas\n  3. Does NOT check if actual code changed via git diff\n  4. Re-runs without code changes still report "newFiles" because it re-analyzes all files\n- **Line 711-712**: Counts files as "new" by comparing file paths between runs\n- **Problem**: Every full re-analysis adds the same files as "new" if previous analysis was incomplete\n- **Line 729**: Counts test cases by createdAt date, not by actual new tests\n\n#### Issue 5: Test-Source Correlation Missing\n- **Problem**: 60+ test files excluded from analysis (line 195)\n- **No Mapping**: TestCase model not linked to CodeMetrics\n- **No Execution Tracking**: test-analyzer.processor.ts never correlates test runs with analyzed files\n- **Missing Data Structure**: No table mapping test files to source files they cover\n\n### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n\n**Database Schema Issues:**\n- CodeMetrics has no historical snapshots (no versioning)\n- No TestCaseMapping or FileTestLink table\n- No baseline/previous run reference\n\n**Service Dependencies:**\n- CodeAnalysisProcessor -> Prisma.CodeMetrics.upsert()\n- CodeMetricsService.getAnalysisComparison() queries the same table twice (not comparing actual baselines)\n- WorkersService enqueues jobs but has no execution chain\n\n**File Scan Logic Constraints:**\n- git ls-files doesn't respect .gitignore for coverage filtering\n- isSourceFile() (line 190) hardcodes extension list\n- No language detection beyond extension\n\n### Recommended Implementation Approach\n\n1. **Fix File Scanner** (Priority 1)\n   - Remove test file exclusion from isSourceFile() (line 195)\n   - Separate file analysis from coverage filtering\n   - Track both source AND test files in CodeMetrics\n\n2. **Integrate Jest Coverage** (Priority 1)\n   - Add Jest CLI execution to analyzeProject()\n   - Parse coverage-final.json CORRECTLY with proper path normalization\n   - Store coverage separately per file in CodeMetrics.testCoverage\n\n3. **Remove Hardcoded Values** (Priority 1)\n   - Audit CodeMetrics table for manually set values\n   - Enforce coverage must come from Jest output only\n   - Delete any records with hardcoded values\n\n4. **Implement Proper Baseline Comparison** (Priority 2)\n   - Create CodeMetricsSnapshot table (timestamps all metrics)\n   - Store full git diff between runs in Commit model\n   - Calculate deltas from actual code changes, not file re-analysis\n\n5. **Add Test-Source Correlation** (Priority 2)\n   - Create FileTestLink (filePath -> testCaseId mapping)\n   - Update test-analyzer.processor.ts to populate this table\n   - Enable coverage gap analysis by file\n\n### Known Code Patterns\n\n- **Coverage Loading**: Lines 569-686 in code-analysis.processor.ts show path normalization attempts with multiple prefixes\n- **Complexity Calculation**: Lines 303-329 use simplified regex-based method (not AST parser)\n- **Risk Score Formula**: Line 489: `(complexity * churn * (100 - maintainability)) / 100`\n- **Metrics Aggregation**: metrics-aggregator.processor.ts uses story.metadata for storage (not dedicated tables)\n\n### Test Coverage Status\n- code-analysis-coverage.spec.ts covers path normalization scenarios\n- NO tests for full Jest coverage integration\n- NO tests for delta calculation accuracy\n- NO tests for baseline comparison with real git changes	\N	0	\N	\N	\N	0
