a27cc4da-f1b7-4c59-8813-0311fcdde41e	245e4fc9-e09c-4056-878b-67d66413fe43	1	Track and analyze cache hit/miss rates, tokens cached, and cache efficiency for AI agent executions	## Main Flow\n\n1. Agent execution begins, system records session ID\n2. System monitors token cache reads/writes during execution\n3. Each cache hit/miss is counted\n4. Cache hit rate is calculated: hits / (hits + misses)\n5. Metrics are stored in ComponentRun record\n6. Dashboard displays cache efficiency trends\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**No Cache Available:**\n- Set cacheHits = 0, cacheMisses = total_requests\n- cacheHitRate = 0.0\n\n**Perfect Cache Hit:**\n- All requests served from cache\n- cacheHitRate = 1.0\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Agent execution is in progress\n- ComponentRun record exists\n- Session tracking is enabled\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- Cache metrics (tokensCacheRead, tokensCacheWrite, cacheHits, cacheMisses, cacheHitRate) are recorded\n- Metrics available for analysis and visualization\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- Cache hit rate must be between 0.0 and 1.0\n- Cache tokens must be non-negative integers\n- High cache hit rates indicate efficient prompt reuse	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 10:10:14.806	\N	\N
a1369f9a-1496-4b77-af69-bbfc3c28e9fc	2a703e92-84f5-4b4d-9083-5bbecb30b168	1	Track lines of code added/deleted/modified and measure impact on code complexity and test coverage	## Main Flow\n\n1. Before agent starts coding, system captures baseline metrics:\n   - Current cyclomatic complexity of affected files\n   - Current test coverage percentage\n2. Agent makes code changes\n3. System tracks:\n   - Lines added, deleted, modified\n   - Files affected\n4. After completion, system measures:\n   - New cyclomatic complexity\n   - New test coverage percentage\n5. Deltas are calculated and stored\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**No Code Changes:**\n- linesAdded = linesDeleted = linesModified = 0\n- Complexity and coverage remain unchanged\n\n**Test-Only Changes:**\n- linesAdded > 0 (test code)\n- coverageAfter > coverageBefore\n- complexityAfter = complexityBefore\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Code analysis tools available\n- Baseline metrics can be captured\n- Git tracking enabled for file changes\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- Code impact metrics stored in ComponentRun\n- Complexity delta available for quality assessment\n- Coverage improvement tracked\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- Complexity reduction is positive (complexityBefore > complexityAfter)\n- Coverage increase is positive (coverageAfter > coverageBefore)\n- All line counts must be non-negative	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 10:10:15.286	\N	\N
616b4d5d-9697-4b5e-9b05-181bc2e301dc	5b6b59bb-5e58-432a-a949-d354248bbe2e	1	Receive, parse, and store OpenTelemetry events from Claude Code sessions for detailed execution analysis	## Main Flow\n\n1. Claude Code emits OTEL events during execution\n2. OTEL Ingestion Service receives event stream\n3. Service parses event type (api_request, tool_use, etc.)\n4. Service extracts:\n   - Session ID\n   - Timestamp\n   - Event metadata\n   - Tool-specific data (name, parameters, duration, success)\n5. Event is stored in OtelEvent table\n6. Event is flagged for aggregation processing\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**Tool Use Event:**\n- Extract toolName, toolParameters, toolDuration\n- Record toolSuccess or toolError\n- Update tool breakdown statistics\n\n**API Request Event:**\n- Extract token counts\n- Record model ID, temperature\n- Calculate throughput metrics\n\n**Unknown Event Type:**\n- Store raw event data in metadata\n- Log warning for review\n- Mark as processed = false\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- OTEL endpoint configured\n- Database connection available\n- Session mapping exists\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- Event stored in otel_events table\n- Event linked to project\n- Aggregation flag set for processing\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- All events must have session ID and timestamp\n- Events must be idempotent (no duplicates)\n- Processing should not block event ingestion	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 10:10:15.582	\N	\N
e2ec7ca9-c6f0-4da3-ac06-888e91448d16	f8818d28-2fb4-4bd0-bb93-112aad98c60c	1	Aggregate individual tool calls into summary statistics showing tool performance, error rates, and usage patterns	## Main Flow\n\n1. Metrics Aggregation Service polls for unprocessed OTEL events\n2. Service groups events by componentRunId\n3. For each tool used, service calculates:\n   - Total calls count\n   - Error count and error rate\n   - Average duration\n   - Success rate\n4. Tool breakdown JSON is constructed\n5. ComponentRun.toolBreakdown field is updated\n6. Events are marked as processed\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**No Tool Events:**\n- toolBreakdown = {}\n- errorRate = 0, successRate = 1.0\n\n**All Tools Failed:**\n- errorRate = 1.0\n- successRate = 0.0\n- Alert triggered for review\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- OTEL events ingested and stored\n- ComponentRun record exists\n- Aggregation service running\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- toolBreakdown JSON populated with per-tool stats\n- errorRate and successRate calculated\n- Events marked as aggregated\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- errorRate + successRate should approximate 1.0\n- Tool breakdown must include all unique tools used\n- Aggregation should be idempotent	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 10:10:41.161	\N	\N
29079575-dfbd-47b3-befc-aa3e233185b3	c8533805-5c03-4990-830d-514d06a776a8	1	Calculate and store detailed cost breakdown and performance metrics for agent executions	## Main Flow\n\n1. During execution, system tracks:\n   - Model ID used\n   - Temperature setting\n   - Max tokens configuration\n2. System measures performance:\n   - Time to first token\n   - Tokens per second throughput\n3. System calculates costs:\n   - Input token cost\n   - Output token cost\n   - Cache token cost (if applicable)\n4. costBreakdown JSON is constructed\n5. Stop reason is recorded (end_turn, max_tokens, tool_use, error)\n6. All metrics stored in ComponentRun\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**Cache-Heavy Execution:**\n- Lower input token cost due to cache\n- Cache cost recorded separately\n- Higher overall efficiency\n\n**Max Tokens Reached:**\n- stopReason = 'max_tokens'\n- Output may be incomplete\n- Warning flag set\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Pricing information available\n- Model configuration accessible\n- Execution completed or errored\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- costBreakdown contains {input: $, output: $, cache: $}\n- Performance metrics (timeToFirstToken, tokensPerSecond) recorded\n- Total cost calculated\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- All costs must be in USD\n- Cost breakdown must sum to total cost\n- Performance metrics must be positive numbers	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 10:10:41.376	\N	\N
78dd1f72-6b7e-4d67-ae89-0a480bd7edba	1db323f4-9219-4478-82b3-b8c3cf9e9a66	1	\N	## Description\nUser views the Workflow Analytics Dashboard with proper theme support in both light and dark modes.\n\n## Main Flow\n1. User navigates to /analytics/workflow\n2. System detects current theme (light/dark)\n3. System renders all components with appropriate theme colors:\n   - Cards use bg-card and border-border\n   - Text uses text-fg for primary, text-muted for secondary\n   - Accent colors properly adjust for visibility\n4. User toggles theme\n5. Dashboard immediately updates all colors for readability\n\n## Postconditions\n- All text has WCAG AA compliant contrast ratio (4.5:1 minimum)\n- No hardcoded colors like 'grey.50' that break in dark mode\n- MUI components use theme-aware sx props	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 12:21:19.502	\N	\N
14e5c6d5-53fc-443a-9bba-14e61d789455	8156d467-fef6-4571-a5f3-b61bcaab34a5	1	\N	## Description\nUser filters workflow metrics by date range, aggregation level, workflow selection, and complexity bands.\n\n## Main Flow\n1. User opens filter section\n2. User selects Date Range from wider dropdown (Week/Month/Quarter/Custom)\n3. User selects Aggregate By from wider dropdown (Workflow/Story/Epic/Agent)\n4. User selects specific Workflow from dropdown (or "All Workflows")\n5. User adjusts Business Complexity slider (1-10)\n6. User adjusts Technical Complexity slider (1-10)\n7. System applies all filters and refreshes data\n8. Dashboard displays only metrics matching all filter criteria\n\n## Postconditions\n- Filters persist during session\n- Data updates reactively on filter change\n- Complexity filters enable apples-to-apples comparison	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 12:21:24.116	\N	\N
14d6ad54-30af-4bcd-b1b6-217d82273464	3f52f9c0-1df7-4f36-9187-4f79d2b88653	1	\N	## Description\nUser views KPI tiles with comparison to system-wide averages.\n\n## Main Flow\n1. User views Workflow Analytics Dashboard\n2. System calculates system-wide averages for all KPIs\n3. For each KPI tile, system displays:\n   - Current value (filtered result)\n   - Percentage difference from system average\n   - Color indicator (green for better, red for worse)\n4. User identifies which metrics are above/below average\n5. User makes data-driven decisions based on comparison\n\n## Alternative Flow: No Comparison Data\n1. If insufficient historical data exists\n2. System displays "N/A" for comparison\n3. System shows tooltip explaining why\n\n## Postconditions\n- Clear visual indication of performance vs baseline\n- Helps identify areas needing improvement	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 12:21:41.52	\N	\N
2a38cc15-cf0b-4865-9978-6a3cbdce5258	c94fd915-5cc1-47d0-bcef-fc8f6ebb7726	1	\N	## Main Flow\n\n1. Workflow execution starts, system assigns unique workflow_run_id (UUID)\n2. Orchestrator process begins with its own session_id\n3. Orchestrator spawns agent(s), each with unique component_run_id (UUID)\n4. OTEL events from orchestrator are tagged with workflow_run_id ONLY (no component_run_id)\n5. OTEL events from agents are tagged with both workflow_run_id AND component_run_id\n6. System maintains separate telemetry streams:\n   - WorkflowRun metrics: orchestrator token usage, cost, tool calls\n   - ComponentRun metrics: agent token usage, cost, tool calls\n7. No double-counting: agent costs NOT attributed to orchestrator\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**Single Agent Workflow:**\n- Orchestrator costs remain minimal\n- Agent costs tracked independently\n- Total workflow cost = orchestrator + all agent costs\n\n**Multi-Agent Workflow:**\n- Each agent has distinct component_run_id\n- Orchestrator coordinates but doesn't inherit agent metrics\n- Parallel agent execution tracked separately\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Workflow run record created with UUID\n- Component run records created for each agent with UUID\n- OTEL_RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTES properly set for each process\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- Orchestrator metrics stored in WorkflowRun (tokensUsed, totalCostUsd)\n- Agent metrics stored in ComponentRun (tokensUsed, totalCostUsd, toolBreakdown)\n- Clear separation of concerns in database\n- No manual KPI recording required\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- Orchestrator costs MUST NOT include agent costs\n- Each agent has unique component_run_id\n- workflow_run_id links all components but costs are separate\n- OTEL events without component_run_id belong to orchestrator	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 13:18:59.823	\N	\N
05a638ee-3b37-49de-b6bd-16fd0aed556a	7f2c12a3-6717-4e0a-9a57-647130a422e5	1	\N	## Main Flow\n\n1. Agent completes execution (success or failure)\n2. System detects agent process exit\n3. System automatically calls OTEL aggregation service:\n   - Fetch all unprocessed OtelEvents for this component_run_id\n   - Calculate cache hit rate\n   - Calculate error rate\n   - Aggregate tool breakdown (calls, errors, avgDuration per tool)\n   - Calculate total tokens (input + output)\n   - Calculate total cost (input + output + cache)\n   - Calculate throughput (tokens per second)\n4. ComponentRun record is updated with aggregated metrics\n5. OtelEvents marked as processed (aggregatedAt timestamp set)\n6. Status updated to completed/failed\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**Agent Crashed:**\n- System still aggregates available OTEL events\n- Status set to 'failed'\n- Partial metrics still useful for debugging\n\n**No OTEL Events:**\n- Metrics set to defaults (0 tokens, 0 cost)\n- Warning logged\n- Status still updated\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Component run record exists with UUID\n- OTEL events ingested during execution\n- Aggregation service available\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- ComponentRun.tokensUsed populated automatically\n- ComponentRun.totalCostUsd calculated automatically\n- ComponentRun.toolBreakdown contains per-tool statistics\n- ComponentRun.errorRate and successRate computed\n- ComponentRun.cacheHitRate computed\n- ComponentRun.finishedAt set\n- NO manual metrics recording needed\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- Aggregation MUST happen automatically on close\n- No manual KPI recording in component code\n- All metrics derived from OTEL events only\n- Idempotent: re-running aggregation yields same results	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 13:19:00.082	\N	\N
cf9c9c62-b832-4e3f-a4e9-926b6826d0f4	50cff09f-9d13-4744-9e4c-d9991908fe97	1	\N	## Main Flow\n\n1. Workflow execution completes (all components finished)\n2. System detects workflow completion\n3. System automatically aggregates orchestrator metrics:\n   - Fetch OtelEvents with workflow_run_id but NO component_run_id\n   - These are orchestrator-specific events\n   - Calculate orchestrator token usage\n   - Calculate orchestrator cost\n   - Calculate orchestrator tool usage\n4. WorkflowRun record updated with orchestrator-only metrics\n5. Total workflow metrics computed (orchestrator + sum of all agents)\n6. Status updated to completed/failed/cancelled\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n**No Orchestrator Events:**\n- Orchestrator metrics = 0\n- Only agent metrics exist\n- Valid for simple workflows\n\n**Orchestrator Overhead High:**\n- Identified through OTEL events\n- Indicates potential optimization opportunity\n- Metrics show orchestrator vs agent cost ratio\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Workflow run record exists with UUID\n- All component runs completed or failed\n- OTEL events ingested for orchestrator\n\n## Postconditions\n\n- WorkflowRun.tokensUsed = orchestrator tokens only\n- WorkflowRun.totalCostUsd = orchestrator cost only\n- Total workflow cost available via SQL aggregation\n- OtelEvents marked as processed\n- NO agent costs included in orchestrator metrics\n- NO manual recording required\n\n## Business Rules\n\n- Orchestrator metrics EXCLUDE agent metrics\n- Events with component_run_id belong to agents, not orchestrator\n- Events with only workflow_run_id belong to orchestrator\n- Aggregation automatic on workflow close\n- Manual KPI recording prohibited	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 13:19:00.331	\N	\N
2e8a0894-a005-4ae6-ba70-e365e310ac38	ac850a4f-b7a5-4485-8558-78cc15bb0356	1	Retrieve overall code health metrics for a project including health score, folder aggregates, hotspots, and actionable recommendations.	## Use Case: Get Project Health Metrics\n\n### Actors\n- AI Agent (via MCP tool)\n- Developer (via API)\n- Dashboard (via frontend)\n\n### Preconditions\n- Project exists in the system\n- User has access to the project\n\n### Main Flow\n1. Client requests project health metrics via get_project_health MCP tool or API\n2. System validates project exists\n3. System queries CodeMetrics table for all file metrics\n4. System aggregates metrics by:\n   - Overall project totals (files, LOC)\n   - Top-level folders (backend, frontend, shared)\n   - Subfolders (up to 3 path segments)\n5. System calculates health indicators:\n   - Overall health score (0-100)\n   - Average complexity, maintainability, churn\n   - Code smell density\n6. System identifies critical hotspots (risk > 60)\n7. System generates insights and recommendations\n8. System returns structured JSON response\n\n### Alternative Flow: Empty Metrics (Critical for ST-7)\n1. Client requests project health metrics\n2. System validates project exists\n3. System finds no metrics in CodeMetrics table\n4. System returns valid JSON with:\n   - Zero values for all numeric fields\n   - "Unknown" rating for health\n   - "No data" status for metrics\n   - Empty arrays for folders, subfolders, hotspots\n   - Informative insight about running CodeAnalysisWorker\n   - Recommendation to run code analysis\n5. System does NOT throw an error\n\n### Postconditions\n- Client receives valid JSON response\n- Response structure is consistent whether empty or with data\n- No exceptions thrown for empty database\n\n### Business Rules\n- Health score must be between 0-100\n- Hotspots limited to top 10 by risk score\n- Subfolders limited to top 20 by health score\n- Metrics use LOC-weighted averages for accuracy	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 15:31:57.15	\N	\N
0e940ca5-dd6b-4562-b196-7672dcfc7cea	6da4bddd-13b7-4d4d-8a14-0ea74dd99ffa	1	User sessions remain valid for 24 hours, allowing users to work continuously without frequent re-authentication	# UC-AUTH-001: Extended Session Duration (24-hour timeout)\n\n## Description\nUsers can maintain an active authenticated session for 24 hours without requiring re-authentication, improving user experience for long-running work sessions.\n\n## Actors\n- **Primary**: Authenticated User\n- **Secondary**: Authentication Service, JWT Service\n\n## Preconditions\n- User has valid credentials\n- Authentication service is operational\n- JWT configuration is set to 24-hour expiration\n\n## Main Flow\n1. User successfully logs in to the system\n2. System generates JWT access token with 24-hour expiration\n3. System generates refresh token with 30-day expiration\n4. System stores hashed refresh token in database\n5. System returns both tokens to client\n6. Client stores tokens in localStorage\n7. User continues working within the 24-hour window\n8. All API requests include valid access token in Authorization header\n9. System validates token and grants access to protected resources\n10. Session remains valid for the full 24-hour period\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n### A1: Token Refresh Within 24-Hour Window\n1. Access token approaches expiration (handled automatically)\n2. Client intercepts 401 response from API\n3. Client sends refresh token to /auth/refresh endpoint\n4. System validates refresh token against stored hash\n5. System generates new access token (24-hour expiration)\n6. System generates new refresh token (30-day expiration)\n7. System updates refresh token hash in database\n8. System returns new tokens to client\n9. Client updates tokens in localStorage\n10. Client broadcasts token update to other tabs via BroadcastChannel\n11. Original request is retried with new access token\n12. User continues working seamlessly\n\n### A2: Multiple API Requests During Token Refresh\n1. First request triggers token refresh (401 response)\n2. Subsequent requests occur while refresh is in progress\n3. Subsequent requests are queued in refresh queue\n4. Token refresh completes successfully\n5. All queued requests are resolved with new token\n6. All requests are retried automatically\n7. User experiences no interruption\n\n## Exception Flows\n\n### E1: Refresh Token Expired (30 days exceeded)\n1. Access token expires after 24 hours\n2. Client attempts to refresh using refresh token\n3. Refresh token has exceeded 30-day expiration\n4. System returns 403 Forbidden\n5. Client clears all authentication state\n6. System notifies session expired listeners\n7. Client redirects user to login page\n8. System displays "Session expired" notification\n\n### E2: Refresh Token Invalid or Tampered\n1. Client sends refresh token to /auth/refresh\n2. System cannot match token hash in database\n3. System returns 403 Forbidden ("Access denied")\n4. Client clears authentication state\n5. Client redirects to login page\n\n### E3: User Logged Out in Database\n1. Client attempts token refresh\n2. System finds user.refreshToken is null in database\n3. System returns 403 Forbidden\n4. Client clears authentication state\n5. Client redirects to login page\n\n## Postconditions\n- User session remains valid for 24 hours\n- Access token is automatically refreshed when needed\n- Refresh token is rotated with each refresh for security\n- User can work continuously without interruption\n\n## Business Rules\n- BR-001: Access token expiration: 24 hours (configurable via JWT_EXPIRES_IN)\n- BR-002: Refresh token expiration: 30 days (configurable via JWT_REFRESH_EXPIRES_IN)\n- BR-003: Refresh tokens must be hashed before storage (bcrypt)\n- BR-004: Refresh tokens are rotated on each use (new token issued)\n- BR-005: Only one valid refresh token per user at a time\n- BR-006: Token refresh is automatic and transparent to user\n\n## Technical Implementation\n- **Backend**: NestJS AuthService.getTokens() with configurable expiration\n- **Frontend**: api.client.ts interceptor handles automatic token refresh\n- **Storage**: localStorage for tokens, database for hashed refresh tokens\n- **Configuration**: JWT_EXPIRES_IN=24h, JWT_REFRESH_EXPIRES_IN=30d\n\n## Test Scenarios\n1. User logs in and token has 24-hour expiration claim\n2. User makes API calls throughout 24-hour period - all succeed\n3. Token refresh occurs automatically before expiration\n4. Refresh token is rotated on each refresh operation\n5. Session expires after 24 hours without refresh activity\n6. Multiple concurrent requests during refresh are queued correctly\n7. Invalid refresh token triggers immediate logout\n	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 22:32:23.454	\N	\N
c7cd9def-4770-4cfd-9021-fd9a8d49dc37	9f1f6564-b32d-46cf-8839-c7090b3d2001	1	System automatically detects expired sessions, clears authentication state, and redirects user to login page with clear feedback	# UC-AUTH-002: Session Expiration Detection and Redirect\n\n## Description\nWhen a user's session expires (access token expires and refresh token cannot be renewed), the system automatically detects this condition, clears all client-side authentication state, notifies the user, and redirects them to the login page.\n\n## Actors\n- **Primary**: Authenticated User (whose session has expired)\n- **Secondary**: API Client Interceptor, Authentication Context, Authentication Service\n\n## Preconditions\n- User was previously authenticated\n- User's access token has expired\n- User's refresh token is either expired, invalid, or missing\n- User attempts to make an API request\n\n## Main Flow\n1. User is working in the application\n2. Access token expires (24 hours since last refresh)\n3. User performs action that triggers API request\n4. API request includes expired access token\n5. Backend returns 401 Unauthorized response\n6. API client interceptor detects 401 response\n7. Interceptor attempts to refresh access token\n8. Refresh attempt fails (refresh token expired/invalid)\n9. Interceptor triggers session expiration flow\n10. System clears localStorage (accessToken, refreshToken, user)\n11. System broadcasts LOGOUT to all open tabs via BroadcastChannel\n12. System captures current path (e.g., "/epic-planning")\n13. System notifies session expired listeners with current path\n14. AuthContext receives notification\n15. AuthContext saves redirect path to sessionStorage\n16. AuthContext clears user state\n17. System redirects to /login page\n18. Session expired modal/notification is displayed to user\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n### A1: Session Expires While User is Idle\n1. User leaves application open but inactive\n2. 24 hours pass without any activity\n3. Access token expires\n4. Refresh token also expires (or approaches expiration)\n5. User returns and clicks any protected action\n6. System detects expired session on first API call\n7. Main flow continues from step 6\n\n### A2: Session Expires on Page Refresh\n1. User refreshes browser page\n2. AuthContext initializes and checks for user in localStorage\n3. User exists in localStorage (stale session)\n4. First API request is made during component mounting\n5. Backend returns 401 due to expired token\n6. Token refresh fails\n7. Main flow continues from step 9\n\n## Exception Flows\n\n### E1: Network Error During Session Check\n1. Session expiration detected\n2. Network error occurs before redirect\n3. System still clears local authentication state\n4. System displays connection error notification\n5. User must manually navigate to login or refresh page\n\n### E2: User Already on Login Page\n1. Session expires while user is on login page\n2. System detects current path is "/login"\n3. System does not save redirect path\n4. System clears authentication state\n5. No redirect occurs (already on login page)\n\n### E3: Multiple Tabs - Session Expires in One Tab\n1. User has multiple tabs open\n2. Session expires in Tab A (API call fails)\n3. Tab A clears auth state and broadcasts LOGOUT\n4. Tab B receives LOGOUT broadcast via BroadcastChannel\n5. Tab B clears its user state\n6. Tab B redirects to login page\n7. All tabs are synchronized to logged out state\n\n## Postconditions\n- All client-side authentication state is cleared\n- User is redirected to login page\n- Original path is saved for post-login redirect\n- User is informed about session expiration\n- All open tabs are synchronized to logged out state\n\n## Business Rules\n- BR-001: Session expiration must clear all tokens from localStorage\n- BR-002: Current path must be saved for post-login redirect (except /login, /register)\n- BR-003: Session expiration must be broadcast to all tabs\n- BR-004: User must see clear notification about session expiration\n- BR-005: After session expiration, all API requests must fail until re-authentication\n- BR-006: Expired sessions cannot be resumed; user must re-authenticate\n\n## Technical Implementation\n- **Detection**: axios response interceptor in api.client.ts\n- **Event System**: onSessionExpired callback system with Set of listeners\n- **State Management**: AuthContext subscribes to session expiration events\n- **Storage**: sessionStorage for redirect path, localStorage cleared on expiration\n- **Multi-Tab Sync**: BroadcastChannel with localStorage fallback\n- **Flow**: 401 → refresh attempt → failure → clearAuthState → notifySessionExpired → redirect\n\n## User Experience Considerations\n- User should see a clear "Session expired, please log in again" message\n- Notification should be non-blocking (toast/modal that auto-dismisses)\n- User's work context is preserved via redirect path\n- No data loss for unsaved work (handled by application state management)\n\n## Test Scenarios\n1. Access token expires, refresh token valid → automatic refresh, no redirect\n2. Both tokens expired → immediate redirect to login with notification\n3. Invalid refresh token → immediate redirect to login\n4. Session expires in Tab A → Tab B also logs out and redirects\n5. Session expires on /login page → no redirect, just state clearing\n6. Session expires on /epic-planning → redirect path saved correctly\n7. Multiple concurrent API calls during expiration → all handled correctly\n8. Network error during expiration → graceful degradation\n	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 22:32:23.854	\N	\N
d46d0a3f-27f9-450c-8bfb-33c93b81a50a	60f0ccff-4f7b-4ddb-bfff-c7d9784f77f8	1	After successful login, user is automatically redirected to the page they were trying to access before authentication was required	# UC-AUTH-003: Post-Login Redirect to Intended Destination\n\n## Description\nWhen a user attempts to access a protected route without authentication or after session expiration, the system captures the intended destination and automatically redirects them back to that page after successful login.\n\n## Actors\n- **Primary**: User (authenticated or attempting to authenticate)\n- **Secondary**: Authentication Context, Layout Component, Login Page\n\n## Preconditions\n- User attempts to access a protected route\n- User is either not authenticated or session has expired\n- Routing system is operational\n\n## Main Flow\n1. User attempts to access protected route (e.g., "/epic-planning")\n2. Layout component detects user is not authenticated\n3. System captures current path including query parameters\n4. System saves path to redirectPath state in AuthContext\n5. System saves path to sessionStorage as "redirectAfterLogin"\n6. System redirects user to /login page\n7. User enters valid credentials\n8. Login is successful, tokens are stored\n9. AuthContext retrieves redirect path from state or sessionStorage\n10. System redirects user to originally requested path\n11. System clears redirect path from state and sessionStorage\n12. User arrives at intended destination with full authentication\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n### A1: Custom Redirect Path Provided to Login Function\n1. Application provides explicit redirect path to login function\n2. Example: login(credentials, "/dashboard")\n3. Custom path takes highest precedence\n4. System redirects to custom path instead of stored path\n5. Stored redirect path is cleared\n\n### A2: No Redirect Path Available\n1. User logs in directly from /login page (no previous navigation)\n2. No redirect path exists in state or sessionStorage\n3. System defaults to /dashboard as fallback\n4. User is redirected to /dashboard after login\n\n### A3: Session Expires While Working\n1. User is on /epic-planning page\n2. Session expires during API call\n3. API interceptor captures current path (/epic-planning)\n4. System saves path to sessionStorage\n5. User is redirected to /login\n6. User logs in successfully\n7. System redirects back to /epic-planning\n8. User resumes work from same location\n\n### A4: Direct URL Access Without Authentication\n1. User types or bookmarks protected URL (e.g., /story/ST-123)\n2. User is not authenticated\n3. Browser attempts to navigate to /story/ST-123\n4. Layout detects no authentication\n5. System saves /story/ST-123 as redirect path\n6. User is redirected to /login\n7. User logs in\n8. User is redirected to /story/ST-123 automatically\n\n## Exception Flows\n\n### E1: Redirect Path is Login or Register Page\n1. System captures redirect path\n2. Path is "/login" or "/register"\n3. System recognizes these as non-protected routes\n4. System does NOT save these paths\n5. After login, user is redirected to /dashboard instead\n6. Prevents redirect loops\n\n### E2: Malformed or Invalid Redirect Path\n1. Redirect path contains invalid characters or format\n2. System attempts to navigate to saved path\n3. React Router encounters error\n4. System falls back to /dashboard redirect\n5. Error is logged for debugging\n\n### E3: Multiple Tabs - Different Redirect Paths\n1. User has Tab A on /epic-planning, Tab B on /timeline\n2. Session expires in both tabs\n3. Tab A saves /epic-planning as redirect path\n4. Tab B saves /timeline as redirect path (overwrites)\n5. User logs in from Tab A\n6. Tab A redirects to /timeline (last saved path)\n7. Tab B receives LOGIN broadcast and updates state\n8. Both tabs are authenticated but may be on different pages\n\n## Postconditions\n- User is authenticated with valid session\n- User is on the page they originally intended to access\n- Redirect path is cleared from storage\n- User can continue their workflow seamlessly\n\n## Business Rules\n- BR-001: Redirect path must include full pathname and query parameters\n- BR-002: Login and register pages must not be saved as redirect paths\n- BR-003: Custom redirect path takes precedence over stored path\n- BR-004: Default redirect destination is /dashboard\n- BR-005: Redirect path precedence: custom > state > sessionStorage > default\n- BR-006: Redirect path is cleared after successful redirect\n- BR-007: Empty path ("/") should not be saved as redirect path\n\n## Technical Implementation\n- **Path Capture**: Layout component useEffect monitors authentication status\n- **Storage**: \n  - Primary: redirectPath state in AuthContext\n  - Backup: sessionStorage "redirectAfterLogin"\n- **Retrieval**: Login function checks custom param → state → sessionStorage → default\n- **Navigation**: React Router navigate with replace: true to prevent back button issues\n- **Path Format**: pathname + search (e.g., "/planning?projectId=abc-123")\n\n## User Experience Benefits\n- No need to navigate back to intended page after login\n- Seamless workflow continuation after session expiration\n- Direct URL bookmarks work correctly\n- Query parameters are preserved (important for project/story context)\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n### Path Capture (Layout.tsx)\n```typescript\nuseEffect(() => {\n  if (!loading && !isAuthenticated) {\n    const currentPath = location.pathname + location.search;\n    if (currentPath !== '/login' && currentPath !== '/register' && currentPath !== '/') {\n      setRedirectPath(currentPath);\n      sessionStorage.setItem('redirectAfterLogin', currentPath);\n    }\n    navigate('/login');\n  }\n}, [isAuthenticated, loading]);\n```\n\n### Path Retrieval (AuthContext.tsx)\n```typescript\nconst login = async (credentials, customRedirectPath?) => {\n  // Login succeeds...\n  const pathToRedirect = customRedirectPath\n    || redirectPath\n    || sessionStorage.getItem('redirectAfterLogin')\n    || '/dashboard';\n  \n  setRedirectPath(null);\n  sessionStorage.removeItem('redirectAfterLogin');\n  navigate(pathToRedirect, { replace: true });\n};\n```\n\n## Test Scenarios\n1. Direct access to /epic-planning → login → redirected to /epic-planning\n2. Session expires on /story/ST-123 → login → redirected to /story/ST-123\n3. Navigate from /login directly → login → redirected to /dashboard\n4. Access /login with no prior session → login → redirected to /dashboard\n5. Query parameters preserved: /planning?projectId=123 → login → /planning?projectId=123\n6. Custom redirect provided: login(creds, "/timeline") → redirected to /timeline\n7. Redirect path is /login → login → redirected to /dashboard (no loop)\n8. Multiple tabs scenario → last-saved path wins\n	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 22:32:24.174	\N	\N
b90100bb-6f13-4237-946d-a442054d0647	cc898521-13f8-4d5c-b9f4-e3bc4a9b407e	1	Authentication state is synchronized across all browser tabs, ensuring consistent user experience when logging in, logging out, or refreshing tokens	# UC-AUTH-004: Multi-Tab Session Synchronization\n\n## Description\nWhen a user has multiple application tabs open, authentication state changes (login, logout, token refresh) in one tab are immediately propagated to all other tabs, ensuring consistent authentication status across the entire browser session.\n\n## Actors\n- **Primary**: User with multiple browser tabs open\n- **Secondary**: BroadcastChannel API, LocalStorage, AuthContext, API Client\n\n## Preconditions\n- User has application open in multiple browser tabs\n- Browser supports BroadcastChannel API (or falls back to storage events)\n- All tabs are from the same origin\n\n## Main Flow - Login Synchronization\n1. User has Tab A (logged out) and Tab B (logged out) open\n2. User logs in via Tab A\n3. Tab A stores tokens in localStorage\n4. Tab A creates BroadcastChannel message with type: "LOGIN"\n5. Tab A broadcasts LOGIN event to all tabs\n6. Tab B receives LOGIN broadcast via BroadcastChannel\n7. Tab B reads updated user data from localStorage\n8. Tab B updates its AuthContext state with user\n9. Tab B updates UI to show authenticated state\n10. Both tabs now show user as logged in\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n### A1: Logout Synchronization\n1. User is authenticated in Tab A and Tab B\n2. User clicks logout in Tab A\n3. Tab A clears tokens from localStorage\n4. Tab A broadcasts LOGOUT event via BroadcastChannel\n5. Tab B receives LOGOUT broadcast\n6. Tab B clears its user state (setUser(null))\n7. Tab B redirects to /login page\n8. Both tabs are now logged out and on login page\n\n### A2: Token Refresh Synchronization\n1. Tab A makes API call that triggers token refresh\n2. Tab A receives new tokens from refresh endpoint\n3. Tab A updates tokens in localStorage\n4. Tab A broadcasts TOKEN_UPDATED via BroadcastChannel\n5. Tab B receives TOKEN_UPDATED broadcast\n6. Tab B reads updated tokens from localStorage\n7. Tab B calls authService.getCurrentUser() to refresh state\n8. Tab B updates user state\n9. Both tabs continue with fresh tokens\n\n### A3: Fallback to Storage Events (BroadcastChannel not supported)\n1. Browser doesn't support BroadcastChannel API\n2. System catches error during channel creation\n3. System falls back to storage event listener\n4. Tab A modifies localStorage (sets "auth_event")\n5. Browser fires storage event to other tabs\n6. Tab B receives storage event\n7. Tab B parses event data and updates state accordingly\n8. Same synchronization behavior achieved\n\n### A4: Session Expiration in One Tab\n1. Tab A makes API call that results in 401\n2. Tab A attempts token refresh, fails\n3. Tab A clears localStorage tokens\n4. Tab A broadcasts LOGOUT via BroadcastChannel\n5. Tab B receives LOGOUT broadcast\n6. Tab B immediately clears state and redirects to login\n7. Both tabs show expired session\n\n## Exception Flows\n\n### E1: BroadcastChannel Not Supported, Storage Events Disabled\n1. BroadcastChannel fails to initialize\n2. Storage event listener added as fallback\n3. Storage events are blocked by browser settings\n4. Tab synchronization fails\n5. Each tab maintains independent auth state\n6. User may see inconsistent states across tabs\n7. System logs warning about synchronization failure\n\n### E2: Race Condition - Simultaneous Login in Multiple Tabs\n1. User submits login in Tab A\n2. User simultaneously submits login in Tab B\n3. Both tabs receive tokens from backend\n4. Both tabs update localStorage (last write wins)\n5. Both tabs broadcast LOGIN event\n6. Both tabs receive both broadcasts\n7. Final state converges to consistent logged-in state\n\n### E3: Broadcast Received Before LocalStorage Update\n1. Tab A updates tokens in localStorage\n2. Tab A broadcasts TOKEN_UPDATED\n3. Tab B receives broadcast before localStorage write completes\n4. Tab B reads stale data from localStorage\n5. Tab B updates to stale state briefly\n6. Next storage sync corrects the state\n\n### E4: Tab B is Frozen/Suspended\n1. Browser suspends Tab B to save resources\n2. Tab A logs out and broadcasts LOGOUT\n3. Tab B doesn't receive broadcast (suspended)\n4. User switches to Tab B\n5. Tab B resumes, sees no tokens in localStorage\n6. Tab B's AuthContext initialization detects no auth\n7. Tab B redirects to login (correct state achieved)\n\n## Postconditions\n- All tabs reflect the same authentication state\n- User state is consistent across browser tabs\n- Tokens in localStorage are synchronized\n- UI updates reflect current authentication status\n\n## Business Rules\n- BR-001: Authentication events must be broadcast to all same-origin tabs\n- BR-002: BroadcastChannel is primary sync mechanism, storage events are fallback\n- BR-003: Event types: LOGIN, LOGOUT, TOKEN_UPDATED\n- BR-004: All tabs must respond to logout broadcasts immediately\n- BR-005: Channel name is "auth_channel" for all tabs\n- BR-006: Storage event key is "auth_event" for fallback mechanism\n- BR-007: Tabs must close BroadcastChannel on component unmount\n\n## Technical Implementation\n\n### BroadcastChannel Approach (Primary)\n- **Channel Name**: "auth_channel"\n- **Message Format**: `{ type: "LOGIN" | "LOGOUT" | "TOKEN_UPDATED", timestamp?: number }`\n- **Initialization**: In AuthContext useEffect on mount\n- **Cleanup**: Close channel on unmount\n- **Broadcasting**: api.client.ts and AuthContext\n- **Receiving**: AuthContext onmessage handler\n\n### Storage Events Approach (Fallback)\n- **Event Key**: "auth_event" or "accessToken" changes\n- **Trigger**: localStorage.setItem() in one tab triggers event in others\n- **Limitation**: Doesn't fire in the tab that made the change\n- **Detection**: Check for BroadcastChannel support with try-catch\n\n### Synchronization Points\n1. **Login**: AuthProvider.login() broadcasts LOGIN\n2. **Logout**: AuthProvider.logout() broadcasts LOGOUT\n3. **Token Refresh**: api.client.refreshAccessToken() broadcasts TOKEN_UPDATED\n4. **Session Expiration**: api.client.clearAuthState() broadcasts LOGOUT\n\n## Browser Compatibility\n- **BroadcastChannel**: Chrome 54+, Firefox 38+, Edge 79+, Safari 15.4+\n- **Storage Events**: All modern browsers (IE 8+)\n- **Graceful Degradation**: Automatic fallback to storage events\n\n## User Experience Benefits\n- Consistent authentication state across all tabs\n- No confusion about logged in/out status\n- Automatic propagation of session expiration\n- Seamless token refresh doesn't require user action\n- Logging out in one tab secures all tabs immediately\n\n## Test Scenarios\n1. Login in Tab A → Tab B updates to logged in automatically\n2. Logout in Tab A → Tab B redirects to login page\n3. Token refreshes in Tab A → Tab B receives new token\n4. Session expires in Tab A → Tab B also logs out\n5. BroadcastChannel not supported → storage events work correctly\n6. Open new tab while logged in → new tab shows authenticated state\n7. Close all tabs → reopen → auth state persists from localStorage\n8. Multiple rapid auth state changes → all tabs converge to final state\n9. Suspend Tab B, logout Tab A, resume Tab B → Tab B logs out correctly\n10. Network disconnect, login in Tab A → Tab B updates when online\n	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 22:32:24.443	\N	\N
26c13384-8d85-4131-aba1-f41056e5a81b	1af32e48-0703-4401-adc0-4b543d26eeda	1	Users can directly access protected routes via URL, and if not authenticated, are prompted to login and then automatically redirected to the requested page	# UC-AUTH-005: Direct Protected Route Access\n\n## Description\nUsers can navigate directly to any protected route in the application (via bookmark, shared link, or typed URL), and if authentication is required, the system will prompt for login while preserving the intended destination for automatic redirect after successful authentication.\n\n## Actors\n- **Primary**: User (authenticated or unauthenticated)\n- **Secondary**: React Router, Layout Component, AuthContext\n\n## Preconditions\n- Application routing is configured with protected routes under Layout\n- User has browser with the application URL\n- Authentication system is operational\n\n## Main Flow - Unauthenticated Direct Access\n1. User receives link to protected resource (e.g., "/epic-planning")\n2. User clicks link or types URL in browser\n3. Browser navigates to the URL\n4. Application loads and AuthProvider initializes\n5. AuthProvider checks for user in localStorage\n6. No valid authentication found\n7. React Router attempts to render Layout component\n8. Layout's useEffect detects user is not authenticated\n9. Layout captures current path ("/epic-planning")\n10. Layout saves path to sessionStorage "redirectAfterLogin"\n11. Layout saves path to AuthContext redirectPath state\n12. Layout navigates to /login\n13. Login page is displayed with URL context preserved\n14. User enters credentials and logs in\n15. AuthContext retrieves saved redirect path\n16. System redirects to "/epic-planning"\n17. Layout allows rendering (user is authenticated)\n18. User views the originally requested page\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n### A1: Authenticated Direct Access\n1. User is already logged in (valid tokens in localStorage)\n2. User clicks link to "/story/ST-123"\n3. Browser navigates to URL\n4. AuthProvider initializes and finds valid user\n5. Layout checks authentication - user is authenticated\n6. Layout renders normally, showing protected content\n7. No redirect to login occurs\n8. User immediately views /story/ST-123\n\n### A2: Direct Access with Query Parameters\n1. User accesses "/planning?projectId=abc-123&filter=bugs"\n2. User is not authenticated\n3. Layout captures full path with query params\n4. Path saved: "/planning?projectId=abc-123&filter=bugs"\n5. User is redirected to login\n6. User logs in successfully\n7. System redirects to saved path with all query parameters\n8. Page loads with correct project and filter applied\n\n### A3: Direct Access During Active Session\n1. User is authenticated with 12 hours remaining on token\n2. User opens new tab\n3. User types "/timeline" in address bar\n4. New tab loads application\n5. AuthProvider finds valid user in localStorage\n6. Layout permits access immediately\n7. Timeline page renders without login prompt\n\n### A4: Shared Deep Link to Story Details\n1. Team member shares link: "/story/ST-456"\n2. Recipient opens link in browser\n3. Recipient is not logged in\n4. System saves "/story/ST-456" as redirect path\n5. Login page displayed\n6. Recipient logs in with their credentials\n7. System redirects to "/story/ST-456"\n8. Story details page loads with correct story context\n\n## Exception Flows\n\n### E1: Direct Access to Login Page\n1. User navigates to "/login" directly\n2. Layout detects path is "/login"\n3. Layout does NOT save "/login" as redirect path\n4. User sees login page\n5. After login, user is redirected to default ("/dashboard")\n6. Prevents redirect back to login (infinite loop)\n\n### E2: Direct Access to Register Page\n1. User navigates to "/register"\n2. Layout skips saving "/register" as redirect path\n3. Registration flow proceeds normally\n4. After registration, user redirected to "/dashboard"\n\n### E3: Direct Access with Expired Session\n1. User has old bookmark to "/epic-planning"\n2. User's session expired days ago\n3. User clicks bookmark\n4. AuthProvider checks localStorage, finds stale user object\n5. First API call returns 401 Unauthorized\n6. Token refresh attempt fails (refresh token expired)\n7. System clears all auth state\n8. Layout detects no authentication\n9. System saves "/epic-planning" as redirect path\n10. User redirected to login\n11. After login, user returns to "/epic-planning"\n\n### E4: Malformed URL or Non-Existent Route\n1. User accesses "/invalid-route-xyz"\n2. Layout attempts authentication check\n3. User is not authenticated\n4. System saves "/invalid-route-xyz" as redirect path\n5. User redirected to login\n6. User logs in\n7. System attempts redirect to "/invalid-route-xyz"\n8. React Router shows 404 or default error page\n9. User can navigate to valid routes from there\n\n### E5: Root Path Direct Access\n1. User accesses "/" (root path)\n2. React Router has `<Route index element={<Navigate to="/dashboard" />}>`\n3. Immediate redirect to "/dashboard" via router\n4. Layout checks authentication for dashboard\n5. If not authenticated, layout saves "/dashboard" as redirect\n6. User logs in\n7. User arrives at dashboard\n\n## Postconditions\n- User accesses the specific resource they intended to view\n- Authentication state is validated or established\n- URL reflects the requested resource\n- Query parameters and route params are preserved\n- User experience is seamless for authenticated users\n\n## Business Rules\n- BR-001: All routes under Layout component are protected\n- BR-002: /login and /register are public routes\n- BR-003: Root path "/" redirects to "/dashboard"\n- BR-004: Path capture includes pathname + search parameters\n- BR-005: Direct access must work for all protected routes\n- BR-006: Bookmark/shared links must be fully functional after auth\n- BR-007: Query parameters must be preserved through authentication flow\n\n## Technical Implementation\n\n### Route Structure (App.tsx)\n```typescript\n<Routes>\n  <Route path="/login" element={<LoginPage />} />\n  <Route path="/" element={<Layout />}>\n    <Route index element={<Navigate to="/dashboard" />} />\n    <Route path="dashboard" element={<DashboardPage />} />\n    <Route path="epic-planning" element={<EpicPlanningView />} />\n    <Route path="story/:storyKey" element={<StoryDetailPage />} />\n    {/* All routes under Layout are protected */}\n  </Route>\n</Routes>\n```\n\n### Authentication Guard (Layout.tsx)\n```typescript\nuseEffect(() => {\n  if (!loading && !isAuthenticated) {\n    const currentPath = location.pathname + location.search;\n    if (currentPath !== '/login' && currentPath !== '/register' && currentPath !== '/') {\n      setRedirectPath(currentPath);\n      sessionStorage.setItem('redirectAfterLogin', currentPath);\n    }\n    navigate('/login');\n  }\n}, [isAuthenticated, loading, navigate, location]);\n```\n\n### Path Preservation\n- **Full Path**: `location.pathname + location.search`\n- **Storage**: sessionStorage "redirectAfterLogin" (survives page refresh)\n- **State**: AuthContext redirectPath (in-memory)\n- **Retrieval**: Login function checks state → sessionStorage → default\n\n## User Experience Benefits\n- Bookmarks work correctly (no broken links after deployment)\n- Shared links are fully functional\n- Deep linking to specific resources (stories, epics, dashboards)\n- Natural URL-based navigation\n- No confusion about "where did my link take me?"\n- Seamless return to intended content after authentication\n\n## Test Scenarios\n1. Copy/paste protected URL while logged out → login → arrive at URL\n2. Bookmark epic planning page → close browser → reopen bookmark → login → see epic planning\n3. Share story link with colleague → colleague opens → login → see exact story\n4. Direct access to /dashboard while logged out → login → see dashboard\n5. Direct access to /login → login → redirect to dashboard (not back to login)\n6. Access /planning?projectId=X&status=Y → login → query params preserved\n7. Access /story/ST-123 → login → story param (ST-123) preserved\n8. Access invalid route → login → see 404 (not crash)\n9. Access root / → redirect to dashboard logic triggers\n10. Middle-click link (open in new tab) → new tab requires auth if not logged in\n11. Bookmarklet or external link → works same as direct URL access\n	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 22:32:24.743	\N	\N
d4c5fb09-74de-4eec-97d5-eb5d1062eb5f	6e404ff4-ca9d-4d19-b7b2-21f311f4ec6b	1	Access tokens are automatically refreshed before expiration using refresh tokens, providing seamless authentication without user intervention or interruption	# UC-AUTH-006: Automatic Token Refresh Flow\n\n## Description\nWhen an access token expires or is about to expire, the system automatically uses the refresh token to obtain a new access token without requiring user interaction, enabling uninterrupted access to protected resources throughout the session lifetime.\n\n## Actors\n- **Primary**: System (on behalf of authenticated user)\n- **Secondary**: API Client Interceptor, Authentication Service, User (passive)\n\n## Preconditions\n- User is authenticated with valid access token\n- Refresh token is stored in localStorage\n- Refresh token is not expired (within 30-day window)\n- User has active refresh token hash in database\n\n## Main Flow\n1. User is authenticated and working in application\n2. Access token expires (24 hours since issuance/last refresh)\n3. User triggers action that makes API request\n4. API request includes expired access token in Authorization header\n5. Backend validates token, determines it's expired\n6. Backend returns 401 Unauthorized response\n7. API client response interceptor catches 401 error\n8. Interceptor checks if request has already been retried (_retry flag)\n9. Request has not been retried, proceed with refresh\n10. Interceptor sets isRefreshing flag to true\n11. Interceptor retrieves refresh token from localStorage\n12. Interceptor calls POST /auth/refresh with refresh token\n13. Backend validates refresh token against database hash\n14. Backend generates new access token (24h expiration)\n15. Backend generates new refresh token (30d expiration)\n16. Backend updates user's refresh token hash in database\n17. Backend returns { accessToken, refreshToken }\n18. Interceptor receives new tokens\n19. Interceptor updates localStorage with new tokens\n20. Interceptor broadcasts TOKEN_UPDATED to other tabs\n21. Interceptor updates original request's Authorization header\n22. Interceptor retries original request with new access token\n23. Original request succeeds with fresh token\n24. Response is returned to user's action\n25. User's action completes successfully (seamless)\n26. Interceptor sets isRefreshing flag to false\n\n## Alternative Flows\n\n### A1: Multiple Concurrent Requests During Refresh\n1. First request (Request A) triggers token refresh (401)\n2. Request A sets isRefreshing = true\n3. Second request (Request B) also receives 401\n4. Request B sees isRefreshing = true\n5. Request B creates Promise and adds to refreshQueue\n6. Third request (Request C) also receives 401\n7. Request C also queued in refreshQueue\n8. Token refresh completes successfully\n9. New token returned from refresh endpoint\n10. Request A updates Authorization header and retries\n11. Interceptor resolves all queued promises with new token\n12. Request B updates header and retries\n13. Request C updates header and retries\n14. All three requests succeed\n15. refreshQueue is cleared\n16. isRefreshing set to false\n\n### A2: Proactive Refresh Before Expiration (Not Implemented)\n1. System could decode JWT and check expiration time\n2. If token expires in < 5 minutes, proactively refresh\n3. Avoids any 401 errors entirely\n4. More complex implementation\n5. Current implementation: reactive (refresh on 401)\n\n### A3: Refresh Token About to Expire\n1. Access token expires, triggers refresh\n2. Refresh token has 29 days remaining\n3. Refresh succeeds, new tokens issued\n4. New refresh token resets 30-day expiration\n5. As long as user is active, refresh token never expires\n6. Continuous access maintained\n\n## Exception Flows\n\n### E1: Refresh Token Expired\n1. Access token expires, 401 received\n2. Interceptor attempts to refresh\n3. Refresh token is older than 30 days\n4. Backend cannot validate refresh token (expired)\n5. Backend returns 403 Forbidden\n6. Interceptor catches refresh failure\n7. Interceptor calls clearAuthState()\n8. All tokens removed from localStorage\n9. Session expired event fired\n10. All queued requests rejected with error\n11. User redirected to login page\n12. Notification: "Session expired, please log in"\n\n### E2: Refresh Token Invalid or Tampered\n1. Access token expires, refresh attempted\n2. Refresh token doesn't match database hash\n3. Backend returns 403 Forbidden ("Access denied")\n4. Interceptor treats as failed refresh\n5. clearAuthState() called\n6. User logged out and redirected to login\n\n### E3: Refresh Token Revoked (User Logged Out)\n1. User clicks logout in another session/device\n2. Backend sets user.refreshToken = null in database\n3. Later, in this session, access token expires\n4. Interceptor attempts refresh\n5. Backend finds no refresh token for user\n6. Backend returns 403 Forbidden\n7. Session cleared, user redirected to login\n\n### E4: Network Error During Refresh\n1. Access token expires, refresh initiated\n2. Network connection lost during refresh request\n3. Refresh request fails with network error\n4. Interceptor catches error\n5. clearAuthState() called (assumes session invalid)\n6. User redirected to login\n7. May lose in-progress work\n8. Alternative: Could retry refresh with exponential backoff\n\n### E5: Refresh While Original Request is Auth Endpoint\n1. User is on login page, token expired in background\n2. User submits login form\n3. POST /auth/login receives 401 (shouldn't happen)\n4. Interceptor attempts refresh for login request\n5. Refresh fails (no valid tokens)\n6. Login request fails\n7. User sees error message\n8. Edge case: unlikely but possible\n\n### E6: Multiple Tabs, Refresh Conflict\n1. Tab A and Tab B both have expired tokens\n2. Both make API requests simultaneously\n3. Tab A starts refresh, sets isRefreshing = true\n4. Tab B starts refresh independently (separate context)\n5. Both call refresh endpoint\n6. Backend generates tokens twice\n7. Second refresh overwrites first in database\n8. Tab A gets tokens_v1, Tab B gets tokens_v2\n9. Tab A broadcasts TOKEN_UPDATED with tokens_v1\n10. Tab B broadcasts TOKEN_UPDATED with tokens_v2\n11. Final state: all tabs have tokens_v2 (last write wins)\n12. Works correctly despite race condition\n\n## Postconditions\n- User has fresh access token valid for 24 hours\n- User has new refresh token valid for 30 days\n- Original API request completed successfully\n- User experienced no interruption or error\n- All queued requests during refresh completed\n- Other tabs synchronized with new tokens\n\n## Business Rules\n- BR-001: Token refresh is automatic and transparent to user\n- BR-002: Refresh is triggered on 401 Unauthorized response\n- BR-003: Only one refresh operation at a time per API client instance\n- BR-004: Concurrent requests are queued during refresh\n- BR-005: Original request is retried with new token after refresh\n- BR-006: Request retry is attempted only once (_retry flag)\n- BR-007: Failed refresh results in immediate logout\n- BR-008: Refresh tokens are rotated (new token issued each refresh)\n- BR-009: Old refresh token is invalidated after successful refresh\n- BR-010: Token updates are broadcast to all tabs\n\n## Technical Implementation\n\n### Response Interceptor (api.client.ts)\n```typescript\nthis.client.interceptors.response.use(\n  (response) => response,\n  async (error: AxiosError) => {\n    const originalRequest = error.config as Config & { _retry?: boolean };\n    \n    if (error.response?.status === 401 && !originalRequest._retry) {\n      originalRequest._retry = true;\n      \n      if (this.isRefreshing) {\n        // Queue this request\n        return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n          this.refreshQueue.push({ resolve, reject });\n        }).then(token => {\n          originalRequest.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${token}`;\n          return this.client(originalRequest);\n        });\n      }\n      \n      this.isRefreshing = true;\n      \n      try {\n        const newToken = await this.refreshAccessToken();\n        if (newToken) {\n          originalRequest.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${newToken}`;\n          this.refreshQueue.forEach(({ resolve }) => resolve(newToken));\n          this.refreshQueue = [];\n          return this.client(originalRequest);\n        }\n      } catch (refreshError) {\n        this.refreshQueue.forEach(({ reject }) => reject(refreshError));\n        this.clearAuthState();\n        notifySessionExpired();\n        return Promise.reject(refreshError);\n      } finally {\n        this.isRefreshing = false;\n      }\n    }\n    \n    return Promise.reject(error);\n  }\n);\n```\n\n### Refresh Endpoint (Backend)\n```typescript\nasync refreshTokens(userId: string, refreshToken: string) {\n  const user = await this.prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id: userId } });\n  \n  if (!user || !user.refreshToken) {\n    throw new ForbiddenException('Access denied');\n  }\n  \n  const refreshTokenMatches = await bcrypt.compare(refreshToken, user.refreshToken);\n  \n  if (!refreshTokenMatches) {\n    throw new ForbiddenException('Access denied');\n  }\n  \n  const tokens = await this.getTokens(user.id, user.email, user.role);\n  await this.updateRefreshToken(user.id, tokens.refreshToken);\n  \n  return tokens;\n}\n```\n\n## Performance Considerations\n- Refresh adds ~100-300ms latency to the first request after expiration\n- Queued requests wait for single refresh to complete\n- No impact on requests while token is valid\n- Minimal overhead: one extra API call per 24-hour period\n\n## Security Considerations\n- Refresh token rotation prevents token replay attacks\n- Refresh tokens are hashed in database (bcrypt)\n- Expired refresh tokens cannot be reused\n- Failed refresh immediately clears all auth state\n- Refresh endpoint validates user exists and token matches\n\n## User Experience\n- **Transparent**: User never sees token refresh happening\n- **Seamless**: No interruption to workflow\n- **No Errors**: Failed actions don't happen (refresh saves them)\n- **Fast**: Minimal latency impact (queued requests wait briefly)\n- **Reliable**: Works even with many concurrent requests\n\n## Test Scenarios\n1. Access token expires → single API call → auto-refresh → request succeeds\n2. Three concurrent API calls with expired token → one refresh → all succeed\n3. Refresh token valid → refresh succeeds, new tokens issued\n4. Refresh token expired → refresh fails, user logged out\n5. Invalid refresh token → immediate logout and redirect\n6. Network error during refresh → user logged out (graceful failure)\n7. Refresh in Tab A → Tab B receives TOKEN_UPDATED broadcast\n8. Request A triggers refresh, Request B queued → both complete successfully\n9. Refresh endpoint called directly (manual test) → tokens rotated correctly\n10. Multiple refreshes in sequence (24h apart) → each succeeds, tokens rotate\n11. User logs out in another session → refresh fails with 403\n	\N	5269e325-16c7-4400-85a8-215aee7a2074	2025-11-17 22:32:24.974	\N	\N
